column168: DURING TRANSLOADING, 2 DRUMS WERE DISCOVERED LEAKING.  THEY WERE OVERPACKED AND THE SPILLED MATERIAL ABSORBED. THE PIN HOLES WERE CLOSE TO SEAMS ON THE DRUMS BUT DID NOT APPEAR TO BE ASSOCIATED WITH POOR WELDING.

column42: HYDROGEN, PEROXIDE, AQUEOUS SOLUTIONS WITH MORE THAN 40 PERCENT BUT NOT MORE THAN 60 PERCENT HYDROGEN PEROXIDE (STABILIZED AS NECESSARY)
column168: AT 22:00 HOURS THE LEAK WAS DISCOVERED BY JIMMY CHAMBLES, MY LEADER MAN, WHILE PLACARDING THE TRAILER.   I OBTAINED THE HAZMAT BILLS FROM THIS TRAILER AND REALIZED THERE WERE TWO HAZMAT SHIPMENTS ON THE TRAILER.  BOTH WERE LOADED ON THE LAST EIGHT FEET OF THE TRAILER.  I SECURED THE AREA CHECKED THE EMERGENCY RESPONSE GUIDE BOOK.  I OPENED THE TRAILER DOOR AND WAS ABLE TO CONFIRM WHAT WAS LEAKING.  I THEN CLOSED THE TRAILER DOOR AGAIN AND CALLED EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM AT GENERAL OFFICE.  I WAS PUT IN CONTACT WITH EDDIE YANCE.  I EXPLAINED EVERYTHING I KNEW TO HIM AND THEN FOLLOWED HIS INSTRUCTION.  THE INSTRUCTIONS WERE: 1- PUT ON HAZMAT GEAR, 2- TURN THE DRUM OVER TO STOP THE LEAK, 3- CONTAIN THE SPILL WITH OIL DRY, 4- CALL EMERGENCY RESPONSE NUMBER ON THE BOL, 5- KEEP THE AREA SECURE.  I FOLLOWED THESE INSTRUCTION.  I WASN'T ABLE TO GET A RESPONSE FROM THE EMERGENCY RESPONSE #'S THAT WERE ON THE BILL.  I CALLED EDDIE YANCE BACK AND EXPLAINED THIS TO HIM.  HE THEN INSTRUCTED ME TO CONTACT CHEMTRIC BECAUSE WE HAD TO HAVE MSDS DOCUMENTS.  MAYBE HE COULD OBTAIN THEM FOR US.  I FOLLOWED THESE INSTRUCTIONS.  CHEMTRIC WAS VERY HELPFUL AND WAS ABLE TO PROVIDE THIS FOR ME.  HE ALSO SAID THAT HE WAS GOING TO ATTEMPT TO CONTACT THE SHIPPER AND PUT ME IN CONTACT WITH SIMILAR SHIPPERS THAT DEAL WITH HYDROGEN PEROXIDE.  AFTER RECEIVING THE MSDS FROM CHEMTREC I AGAIN PHONED MR. YANCE AND DISCUSSED THIS INFORMATION THAT I HAD OBTAINED.  ON THE SPECIAL PROTECTION INFORMATION PORTION ON THE MSDS IN STATED THAT SELF CONTAINED SUPPLIED AIR WOULD BE NEEDED.  MR. YANCE INSTRUCTED ME TO CALL HEPACO AT THIS POINT AND INFORM THEM THAT WE NEEDED THEIR ASSISTANCE.  I FOLLOWED THESE INSTRUCTIONS - WHILE WAITING FOR HEPACO I RECEIVED A CALL FROM DAVID SWATZ.  HE IS A DUPONT HAZMAT RESPONSE REPRESENTATIVE WHO HAS EXTENSIVE EXPERIENCE IN HAZMAT SPILLS WITH HYDROGEN PEROXIDE.  CHEMTRIC CONTACTED HIM AND EXPLAINED WHAT I HAD.  HE THEN CONTACTED ME.  HE WAS VERY HELPFUL WITH HIS INSTRUCTION AND KNOWLEDGE.  HE EXPLAINED THAT IF THE SPILL WAS IN A WELL VENTILATED AREA WE COULD PROCEED WITH THE CLEAN UP AT A COMPANY LEVEL.  HE EXPLAINED HOW I COULD DO THIS, WITH FULL INSTRUCTION AND CAUTION I WOULD NEED TO FOLLOW.  I THEN CONTACTED MR. YANCE AGAIN AND EXPLAINED THIS CONVERSATION.  MR. YANCE STATED THAT HE TRUSTED DUPONT BECAUSE OF THEIR PAST EXPERIENCE AND GAVE ME THE OKAY TO PROCEED WITH CLEAN UP.  HEPACO SHOWED UP AFTER I FINISHED TALKING WITH MR. YANCE.  I EXPLAINED TO HIM (KEN WALDEN) THAT I RECEIVED ASSISTANCE AND WOULD NOW PERFORM THE CLEAN UP AT OUR COMPANY LEVEL. HE WAS VERY HELPFUL AND AGREED THAT THE CLEAN UP PROCESS THAT EXPLAINED TO HIM WOULD BE PERFECTLY ALRIGHT.  I THEN PROCEEDED WITH THE CLEAN UP.  I FIRST PUT ON ALL HAZMAT PROTECTIVE GEAR.    I THEN MET ALL THE CONTAMINATED AREA DOWN WITH WATER.  I THEN SWEPT UP ALL OF THE OIL DRY THAT WAS USED TO CONTAIN THE SPILL,  AND PLACED IT IN A 55 GALLON RECOVERY DRUM.  THEN I FILLED THE DRUM WITH WATER.  I PLACED THE LEA

column168: ROTARY GAUGE CAME LOSE FROM THE PROPANE TRUCK WHEN THE DRIVER WAS LOADING THE TRUCK.  THERE WAS AN 800 GALLON RELEASE IN VAPOR FORM. THERE WERE NO INJURIES, NO ROAD CLOSURES, NO AIR CLOSURES.  HAZMAT WAS AT THE SITE.  THE RELEASE OCCURRED OVER A 2 1/2 HOUR PERIOD. WHEN THE GAUGE MALFUNCTIONED IT LEFT A 1/2 INCH HOLE IN THE BACK OF THE TRUCK.  THE INCIDENT WAS REPORTED TO THE FEDERAL DEPARTMENT OF TRANSPORTATION.  OUR INCIDENT # IS 528203 AND WAS REPORTED TO MR. SEIGLER.  AUTHORITIES IN CALIFORNIA WERE CALLED.  OUR REPORT NUMBER IS 00-2007 FOR CALIFORNIA.  A NEW GAUGE & HOSE WILL BE INSTALLED ON OUR TRUCK.

column168: DRIVER WAS TRAVELING NORTH ON I-75.  WHEN EXITING TO HIGHWAY 64 (EAST) HE LOST CONTROL OF THE VEHICLE CAUSING IT TO OVERTURN. PIPING AT REAR OF TRAILER BROKE RELEASING APPROXIMATELY 1500 GALLONS OF PRODUCT.  WITNESSES CONTACTED LOCAL POLICE, FIRE AND MEDICAL PERSONNEL.  NOTIFICATION WAS MADE TO  BOTH NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER AND FLORIDA STATE WARNING POINT.

PAIL WAS FOUND BETWEEN TWO PALLETS OF FREIGHT.  THE TOP HAD TO MUCH PRESSURE APPLIED BY OTHER FREIGHT WHICH CAUSED THE PLASTIC TO CRACK AND SEEP OUT THE CRACK.  PRODUCT WAS CONTAINED IN A RECOVERY PAIL.
WHILE UNLOADING, HOSE CAME LOOSE FROM FITTING CAUSING APPROXIMATELY 10 GALLONS OF PRODUCT TO BE LOST.  CLEAN UP PERFORMED BY DRIVER AND PLANT PERSONNEL.  NO FURTHER INCIDENT REPORTED.

WHEN SHIPMENT ARRIVED AT HOUSTON DOCK SEEPAGE WAS NOTED IN TWO BOXES.  INSPECTION REVEALED THAT FIVE GALLON PAILS WITH CRIMP ON LIDS WERE INSIDE BOXES.  AROUND LID SEAL, SHIPPER ATTEMPTED TO SEAL WITH DUCT TAPE THEN PLACED PAILS IN PLASTIC BAGS.  THESE WERE LOADED INTO FIBERBOARD BOXES THEN TAPED SHUT.  IT APPEARS THAT THIS PACKAGING WAS DONE TO DISGUISE IMPROPER SEALING OF ORIGINAL CONTAINERS.

LOADING TRUCK HIT PIPE LOADED ON SILDE.  PIPE SLIDE UP AIR BETWEEN SLANTS IN PALLET THAT WAS USED FOR DUNNAGE AND HIT 5 GALLON PAIL. RAMMING HOLE IN BUCKET.  USED OIL DRY TO ABSORB LIQUID UNLOADED TRUCK CLEANED UP MESS AND RELOAD TRUCK.

SPILL IDENTIFIED WHEN THE TRAILER WAS 3/4 STRIPPED OF ALL FREIGHT BEHIND THE HAZARDOUS MATERIAL. SAW THE MATERIAL FROM THE DRUM AROUND THE BOARDS OF THE PALLET WHICH THE DAMAGED DRUM WAS SITTING ON. THE DAMAGED DRUM WAS ON THE SKID WITH ANOTHER DRUM, WHICH WAS IN GOOD CONDITION BUT ALSO BULGING ON THE BOTTOM. THE DRUMS WERE LIFTED UP IN THE AIR BY A FORKLIFT SINCE THE LEAK HAD STOPPED TO SEE IF WE COULD IDENTIFY WHERE THE LEAK CAME FROM. WE NOTICED A SMALL "STRESS" CRACK ON THE BOTTOM OF THE DRUM WHERE THE MATERIAL CAME FROM. THE MATERIAL IS A THICK GLUE LIKE SUBSTANCE AND THIS WHAT STOPPED THE LEAK. THE BOTTOM OF THE DRUM WAS BULGING OUT DUE TO THE FACT THAT IT CONTAINED 845# OF MATERIAL. RECOMMENDATIONS TO IMPROVE PACKAGING: A STRONGER GAUGE DRUM NEEDS TO BE USED SO THIS AMOUNT OF MATERIAL CAN WITHSTAND TRANSPORTATION.

column42: FIRE EXTINGUISHERS CONTAINING COMPRESSED OR LIQUEFIED GAS
column168: I WAS CALLED TO RESPOND TO THE UNLOAD, BETWEEN DOORS 12 & 13.  THERE WAS A FIRE EXTINGUISHER THAT WAS SPRAYING THE DRY CHEMICAL.  WHEN I ARRIVED, IT WAS NO LONGER SPRAYING, AND THE WHITE RESIDUE FROM THE CHEMICALS WAS FOUND ONLY ON THE INSIDE OF THE BOX CONTAINING THE EXTINGUISHER.  I PLACED THE BOX IN A SPILL TUB AND REMOVED IT TO THE HAZMAT AREA FOR PROCESSING.  I CONCLUDED THE CAUSE OF THE LEAK WAS THE PACKAGE WAS DROPPED AND THE HANDLE ON THE FIRE EXTINGUISHER WAS TEMPORARILY PRESSED.  PRODUCT WAS REPACKAGED IN SALVAGE DRUM AND RTS.  CARDBOARD WITH RESIDUE ON IT WAS PROCESSED THROUGH DMP PROGRAM.
SHIPMENT WAS DROPPED, FLOOR DRY WAS USED TO CLEAN UP THE FLOOR.  THE BOX AND FLOOR DRY WAS PLACED IN A PLASTIC BAG AND PLACED ON A WOODEN PALLET.  PALLET PLACED IN HAZMAT AREA OF WAREHOUSE.

column42: NITRIC ACID OTHER THAN RED FUMING, WITH AT LEAST 65 PERCENT, BUT NOT MORE THAN 70 PERCENT NITRIC ACID
column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 22:30 HOURS I GOT NOTICE FROM A DOCK HAND THAT I HAD A SPILL ON THE LOWER END OF THE DOCK. I WENT TO INVESTIGATE. I FIRST TRIED TO FIND THE BILL. I ASKED SANFORD BROWN WHO CAUSED THE ACCIDENT. HE TOLD ME MATT MAGEE. I SEEN MATT MAGGEE WALKING OUT OF THE BREAK ROOM WITH HIS LUNCH BOX IN HIS HAND. I ASKED MATT FOR THE BILL. HE SAID HE DIDN'T HAVE THE BILL ON THE HAZ MAT SPILL. HE THEN SAID HE WAS FED UP WITH THIS PLACE AND HE QUIT. FINALLY AFTER ABOUT THREE MINUTE. I OBTAINED THE BILL. SEEING THAT THERE WERE SEVERAL DIFFERENT TYPES OF HAZ MAT ON THIS SHIPMENT AND SEEING ALOT OF ACIDS AND OXIDIZERS I EVACUATEDTHE LOWER END OF THE DOCK. DURING THIS TIME I SEEN WHAT MATERIAL HAD BEEN BUSTED. I CHECKED THE EMERGENCY RESPONSE GUIDE BOOK. I KEPT ALL EMPLOYEES OFF THE LOWER END BECAUSE OF THE INFORMATION I GATHERED ON THE MATERIAL. I THEN CALLED OUR EMERGENCY RESPONSE NUMBER AT THE GENERAL OFFICE AND WAS PUT IN TOUCH WITH EDDIE YANCE. I THEN GAVE HIM ALL THE INFORMATION I HAD AND FOLLOWED HIS INSTRUCTIONS. THEY WERE AS FOLLOWS 1ST SECURE THE AREA WITH TAPE OR ROPE APPROXIMATELY 15 FEET AROUND THE SPILL IN ALL DIRECTION. ALSO LAY DOWN ADSORBENT MATERIAL TO PREVENT THE SPILL FROM SPREADING. 2ND CALL CHEMTRIC TO GET AN MSDS. 3RD TRY AND CONTACT REAGENTS. 4TH LOOK OVER THE MSDS TO SEE IF WE WILL NEED ASSISTANCE IN THE CLEAN UP OR IF WOULD BE ABLE TO CLEAN UP AT COMPANY LEVEL. I FOLLOWED THESE INSTRUCTIONS. WHEN I CALLED CHEMTRIC I WAS CONNECTED WITH JEFFREY BANMAN. I EXPLAINED EVERYTHING TO HIM. HE WASN'T ABLE TO OBTAIN A MSDS FROM REAGENTS. HE SENT ME THE MSDS THAT HE DID HAVE ON THE MOST POTENT SOLUTION OF SODIUM HYDROXIDE COULD FIND. WHILE LOOKING OVER THIS MSDS HE EXPLAINED TO ME THAT WE COULD CLEAN THIS UP AT A COMPANY LEVEL. HIS INSTRUCTIONS WERE AS FOLLOWS. PUT ON RUBBER GLOVES, APRON AND FACE AND EYE PROTECTION. LAY DOWN ABSORBENT ON ALL CONTAMINATED AREA. GET ALL OF THE MATERIAL SWEPT UP AND CONTAINED IN A RECOVERY CONTAINER. I FOLOWED THESE INSTRUCTIONS ON THE CLEAN-UP. I WASN'T ABLE TO GET IN TOUCH WITH REAGENTS. DURING THE CLEAN-UP, ROBERT WESTBROOK WAS ABLE TO MAKE OUT A UN# THAT WAS DIFFERENT FROM WHAT I HAD REPORTED. THE ACID HAD BURNED OFF 80% OF THE LABLES ON THE BUSTED CONTAINERS, BUT ON A BUSTED PIECE. OF GLASS HE NOTICED A UN# 2031. I HAD REPORTED THE SPILL TO BE SODIUM HYDROXIDE (8), UN 1824, PGII. THE DESCRIPTION ON THE UN 2031 WAS NITRIC ACID. HOWEVER THERE IS A 0 UNDER THE SHIPPING UNITS. AFTER FUTHER INVESTIGATION NOTICED THAT THERE WAS A WEIGHT OF 15 LBS BESIDE BOTH DESCRIPTIONS LISTED ABOVE.I HAVE ATTACHED A COPY OF THE BILL. HAND WRITTEN ON THE BOX THAT THESE MATERIALS WERE SHIPPED IN. I FOUND BOTH SODIUM HYDROXIDE AND NITRIC ACID WRITTEN THERE. ROBERT HAD ALREADY HAD EVERYTHING PUT IN THE RECOVERY DRUM. I THEN CALLED CHEMTRIC AGAIN AND EXPLAINED THAT THE WRONG MATERIAL HAD BEEN REPORTED. MR. BANMAN SAID THAT SINCE THE SPILL HAD ALL READY BEEN CLEANED UP, FOR US TO CONTACT REAGENTS IN THE MORNING AND REPORT THE SP

column168: OUR PROPANE TRUCK WAS STRUCK BY A SCHOOL BUS AT INTERSECTION WHEN THE SCHOOL BUS FAILED TO YIELD RIGHT OF WAY. THE COLLISION RESULTED IN A RELEASE. 36 GALLONS OF PROPANE FROM THE MOTOR FUEL TANK. OUR DRIVER STOMPED ON THE GAS PEDAL TO GET THE PROPANE TRUCK AWAY FROM THE SCHOOL BUS AFTER IMPACT. THERE WERE NO INJURIES, NO EVACUATIONS. HICKORY STREET WAS CLOSED FOR ONE HOUR. THE PROPANE WAS DISPERSED INTO THE AIR WITH NO CONSEQUENCES.

A TRUCK WAS BEING OFF LOADED AT THE FACILITY. THE DRUMS WERE PLACED ON A PALLET AND THEN TAKEN TO THE WAREHOUSE BY FORKLIFT. WHILE BEING MOVED TO THE WAREHOUSE THE PALLET BROKE AND A 30 GALLON DRUM FELL TO THE GROUND POPPING OFF THE LID RELEASING 23 GALLONS OF WASTE PETROLEUM NAPHTHA. THE SPILL WAS IMMEDIATELY CLEANED UP WITH ABSORBENT AND CONTAINERIZED. THE SPILL PRODUCED APPROXIMATELY 225 POUNDS OF WASTE WHICH WAS TREATED ALONG WITH THE ORIGINAL WASTE AT THE SAFETY KLEEN FACILITY AT 2120 SOUTH YALE STREET IN SANTA ANA CA. THE SAFETY KLEEN EMPLOYEE RESPONSIBLE FOR UNLOADING THE TRUCK WAS COUNSELED ON DRUM HANDLING AND UNLOADING PROCEDURES TO ENSURE NO MORE FUTURE INCIDENTS.
DOCKMAN PULLED 2ND DRUM OFF TRAILER AND NOTICED IT LEAKING. HE MUST HAVE HIT IT WITH FORKLIFT BLADE PUNCTURING IT.

column168: THE LOADED UNIT WAS ON ROBBIE D WOOD INCS YARD IN DOLOMITE AWAITING FOR DELIVERY APPOINTMENT DAY. SHOP PERSONNEL NOTED THE TRAILER SMOKING AND ON FIRE. THEY BUILT A CONTAINMENT AREA IN THE MIDDLE OF THE LOT SURROUNDED BY ABSORBENT BOOMS. THE FIRE DEPT EXTINGUISHED THE LOAD. AFTER A FEW HOURS WE VACUUMED THE CONTAMINATED LIQUID INTO A VACUUM TANKER & THE LOAD WAS TRANSFERRED INTO 3 ROLLS OF CONTAINERS ALONG W/CLEAN UP MATERIAL. THE LIQUID & SOLID PORTION WAS RETURNED TO THE GENERATOR OF THE HAZARDOUS WASTE. THE FIRE MUST HAVE STARTED FROM A  SPONTANEOUS COMBUSTION OR COMPATIBLE MATERIALS. LOCAL & STATE OFFICIALS NOTIFIED PROMPTLY.

column168: ON MAY 9, 2000 NEAR SLEEPY CREEK WEST VIRGINIA CSXT TRAIN Q34309 WENT INTO EMERGENCY. DURING THE WALK OF THE TRAIN BY THE CREW THEY NOTICED THAT GATX 60989 A LOADED TANK CAR OF HYDROCHLORIC ACID HAD ACID RESIDUE AND LIQUID ON THE SIDE OF THE CAR. THE CAR WAS TAKEN TO THE NEAREST SIDING AT RESTRICTED SPEED AND SET OFF. THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED TO THE INCIDENT. THEY REPORTED FINDING ACID FUMES COMING FROM THE TOP FLANGE ON THE EDUCTION PIPE. BOLTS ON THE FLANGE WERE REPORTED AS TIGHT BUT THE PRODUCT WAS COMING BETWEEN THE BOLTS ON THE SEALING SURFACE. THEY PLACED THE BOLTS AND WASHERS WHICH WERE CORRODED BY THE ACID. WHEN FLANGE WAS TIGHTENED WITH NEW BOLTS AND WASHERS, THE LEAK STOPPED AND THE CAR WAS RELEASED FOR TRANSPORT.

IT IS DIFFICULT TO DETERMINE THE EXACT CAUSE OF THE LEAK WITHOUT EXTENSIVE EXAMINATION WHICH WAS NOT DONE IN THE FIELD. THE CAR WAS BEING SENT TO A REPAIR FACILITY, TEXAS TANK CAR WORKS OF LAGRANGE INC, PLUM, TX ON CSXT WAYBILL 805260 WITH FFRA MOVEMENT AUTHORITY 005104.

column168: THE SHIPMENT CONSISTING OF DRUMS ON PALLETS HAD BEEN LOADED ON AN OUTBOUND TRAILER WHEN SOMEONE NOTICED ONE OF THE DRUMS LEAKING.  THE LEAKING DRUM WAS REMOVED FROM THE PALLET AND THEN REPAIRED WITH ALUMINUM TAPE AND PLACED IN A RECOVERY DRUM.  THE RECOVERY DRUM WAS LOADED BACK WITH THE ORIGINAL SHIPMENT AND SENT TO DESTINATION.  THE CAUSE OF THE SMALL PUNCTURE HOLE IN THE BOTTOM OF THE DRUM WAS DUE TO A NAIL HEAD STICKING UP FROM THE PALLET BOARD WITH THE CONSTANT FRICTION/RUBBING ACTION OF THE NAIL ON THE DRUM BOTTOM CAUSING THE LEAK.  PALLETS SHOULD BE WORTHY OF TRANSPORTING FREIGHT BEFORE SHIPPING THE MATERIAL OUT.

column168: OUR LOADED UNIT ENTERED THE CONSIGNEE PLANT DURING A HEAVY RAIN STORM TO UNLOAD METHYL ETHYL KETOMIXE.  THE PLANT ROAD WAS FLOODED BY THE RAIN.  OUR DRIVER THOUGHT HE WAS ON THE PAVED ROAD.  HE DRIFTED TO THE LEFT INTO A BAR DITCH AND OUR LOADED UNIT LAYED OVER ONTO ITS LEFT SIDE.  WE MADE TEMPORARY PATCH TO THE VACUUM BREAKER TO STOP THE LEAK.  WE UNLOADED THE PRODUCT FROM THE ROLLED OVER TRAILER INTO ANOTHER TRAILER WITH NO FURTHER PROBLEMS.

THE TRUCK AND TRAILER WERE PARKED ON THE SUNOCO TRUCK STOP LOT.  A SUNOCO EMPLOYEE NOTICED MATERIAL LEAKING OUT OF THE TRAILER ONTO THE GROUND.  SUNOCO CALLED THE DEPARTMENT OF TRANSPORTATION WHO THEN CALLED THE DENTON FIRE DEPARTMENT.  OFFICER DON STEWERT THEN CALLED HUB CITY DISPATCH TO REPORT THE LEAK.  THE DENTON FIRE DEPARTMENT CALLED ME 5 MINUTES LATER.  THEY INFORMED ME THAT THE LEAK WAS COMING OUT OF THE REAR VALVE AT A RATE OF 1 GAL. PER HOUR THEY ESTIMATED THAT THERE WAS APROX. 1-2 GALS ALREADY ON SOFT GROUND, NO RUNOFF CONCERN, COVERING A 10FT BY 4FT AREA.  RANDY HALL, JAMES MARSHALL, ANDY FIELDS, AND MYSELF DISCUSSED THE SITUATION AND DECIDED TO CONTACT EAGLE'S FT WORTH OFFICE TO HAVE A REMEDIATION CREW DISPATCHED TO THE SCENE.  THE DRIVER, WHO WAS ON HIS 8-HOUR BREAK IN DALLAS, WAS THEN NOTIFIED AND INSTRUCTED TO REPORT TO THE SCENE.  EAGLE ARRIVED ON THE SCENE APROX. 30 MIN. AFTER OUR CALL TO THEM.  THEY INSPECTED THE VALVE, STOPPED THE LEAK, AND RECOVERED APROX. 3 GALS OF MATERIAL FROM THE GROUND.  THE DRIVER ARRIVED AT APROX. 5:45 AND WAS ISSUED A CITATION DUE TO THE LEAK BY THE DENTON FIRE DEPARTMENT.  CAUSE OF INCIDENT:  IT WAS DETERMINED THAT SOLID MATERTIAL WAS LODGED IN THE INTERNAL VALVE DURING UNLOADING WHICH ALLOWED LIQUID TO PASS THROUGH TO THE EXTERNAL GATE VALVE, WHEN THE TRAILER WAS PARKED EARLY THURSDAY MORNING THERE WAS NOT A LEAK. WHILE SITTING IN THE MID-DAY SUN PRESSURE BUILT UP WHICH FORCED LIQUID THROUGH THE EXTERNAL GATE VALVE AND INTO THE OUTER CAP WHICH DIDN'T HAVE A GASKET THEREFORE ALLOWING WASTE TO DRIP OUT AND CREATE THE SPILL.  THE DRIVER PULLED A VACUUM ON THE TRAILER WHICH CLEARED THE IN AND EXTERNAL VALVES, DRIVER THEN CLOSED THE INTERNAL VALVE LEAVING THE OUTER VALVE OPENED, RELEASED THE VACUUM TO CHECK THAT THE INTERNAL VALVE WS HOLDING, WHICH IT DID, HE THEN REPLACED 3" GASKET AND CAP WHICH SOLVED THE PROBLEM.  EMERGENCY RESPONSE AND CLEANUP PERFORMED BY:  EAGLE CONSTRUCTION PERSONAL PROTECTION EQUIPMENT AND SOME OIL SORB WAS RECOVERED FROM THE SCENE.  EAGLE TRANSPORTED THE DRUM TO SAFETY KLEEN SYSTEMS INC. IN DENTON, TX FOR PROPER DISPOSAL.

column168: (A) CARGO TANK 1334 WAS BEING PREPARED TO BE OFF-LOADED AT THE CONSIGNEE. WHEN THE EXTERNAL VALVE CAP WAS REMOVED IN ORDER TO HOOK-UP UNLOADING FITTINGS AND HOSES, PRODUCT IMMEDIATELY WAS RELEASED.  THE INTERNAL VALVE WAS MALFUNCTIONED, AND WAS NOT HOLDING PRODUCT INSIDE THE CARGO TANK.  AS A RESULT, PRODUCT WE WAS RELEASED ONTO THE GROUND, WHILE SOME PRODUCT WAS CONTAINED IN A CONTAINMENT BUCKET BY THE DRIVER.  AN ESTIMATED 25 TO 35 GALLONS WAS RELEASED. ONCE THE RELEASE WAS CONTAINED, THE SHIPMENT WAS OFF-LOADED.  THE RELEASED MATERIAL WAS CLEANED UP BY THE SHIPPER ACCORDING TO THEIR REQUIREMENTS.

DURING THE PM OPERATIONS THIS SHIPMENT WAS FOUND TO BE LEAKING A SMALL AMOUNT OF WHAT APPEARED TO BE BLOOD.  THE SHIPMENT WAS AN INFECTIOUS SUBSTANCE (6.2) HEPATITUS. A CLEAN HARBORS ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES, INC. (CHESI) VACUUM TRAILER CONTAINING 5000 GALLONS OF HAZARDOUS WASTE WAS ENROUTE FROM CLEAN HARBORS OF BRAINTREE, INC. LOCATED AT 1 HILL RD, IN BRAINTREE, MA TO CLEAN HARBORS ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES, INC. 2900 ROCKERFELLER AVE IN CLEVELAND, OH.  SHORTLY AFTER DEPARTING THE BRAINTREE FACILITY, THE DRIVER OBSERVED A SPLASH FROM THE DOME COVER AREA WHILE AT THE TRAFFIC LIGHT.  THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY APPLIED SPEEDI-DRI TO THE SPILL AREA ON THE GROUND, AND THEN TIGHTENED THE DOME COVER.  LESS THAN 1 QUART OF MATERIAL SPILLED.  THE SPEEDI-DRI WAS SWEPT UP AND PLACED INTO AN APPROVED SALVAGE CONTAINER.  AFTER FURTHER INVESTIGATION IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE DEPARTURE OF THE VACUUM TRAILER, FROM THE BRAINTREE FACILITY WAS DELAYED FOR A PERIOD OF TIME WHILE A VALVE WAS TO BE REPAIRED.  THE DOME COVER WAS LOOSENED IN ORDER TO MAKE THE REPAIR.  THE DRIVER HAD ALREADY COMPLETED HIS PRE-TRIP INSPECTION, AND WAS NOT NOTIFIED BY THE MECHANIC THAT THE DOME COVER HAD BEEN LOOSENED IN ORDER TO REPAIR THE VALVE.

SPILL WAS IMMEDIATELY CONTAINED AND DAMAGED FREIGHT WAS PLACED IN RECOVERY DRUM WAITING FINAL DISPOSITION. FORKLIFT OPERATOR WAS INSTRUCTED TO ALWAYS MAKE SURE FREIGHT IS SECURE BEFORE MOVING AND IF NOT TO TAKE THE TIME AND SECURE.

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Impact with Sharp or Protruding Object (e.g., nails)
column168: UNLOADER WAS REMOVING FREIGHT FROM TRUCK.  HE BROUGHT A PALLET INTO THE TRAILER WITH A FORKLIFT TO PLACE SMALL DRUM ON.  HE PUSHED THE PALLET UP TO THE FREIGHT ON THE FLOOR AND DID NOT REALIZE THAT THERE WAS A NAIL STICKING OUT FROM THE PALLET WHICH SUBSEQUENTLY PUNCTURED THE BOTTOM OF THE POLY DRUM.  DRUM WAS IMMEDIATELY PLACED ON SIDE, PATCHED WITH DRUM PATCH AND PLACED INTO A SMALL SALVAGE DRUM AND RETURNED TO SHIPPER AS INSTRUCTED.  DOCK WORKER WAS INSTRUCTED TO PAY MORE ATTENTION TO PALLETS SELECTED, I.E. NAILS PROTRUDING, BROKEN BOARDS, ETC.

column168: WHEN UNLOADING FREIGHT FORKLIFT OPERATOR PICKED UP PALLET WITH FORKLIFT CAUSING A SUPPORTING BOARD ON PALLET TO BREAK AND PUNCTURE BOX AND ONE INNER GALLON CONTAINER DAMAGED CONTAINER WAS REMOVED AND CONTAINED IN SALVAGE CONTAINER AND RETURNED TO SHIPPER AS PER INSTRUCTED.  USE BETTER PALLET IN FUTURE.

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Impact with Sharp or Protruding Object (e.g., nails)
column168: FREIGHT WAS LOADED ONTO A JUNK PALLET WHICH APPARENTLY HAD A PROTRUDING NAIL WHICH PUNCTURE THROUGH BOX INTO A ONE GALLON INNER CAN.  NAIL ACTED SOMEWHAT LIKE A PLUG THOUGH, ONLY A SMALL AMOUNT LEAKED OUT AND WAS ABSORBED INTO FIBREBOX.  FREIGHT WAS PLACED INTO A RECOVERY CONTAINER AND RETURNED TO SHIPPER AS PER INSTRUCTED.  LOADER NEEDS TO USE BETTER PALLETS AND/ OR CHECK AND INSPECT THE ONES THAT ARE BEING USED.

column42: HYDROGEN PEROXIDE, AQUEOUS SOLUTIONS WITH NOT LESS THAN 20 PERCENT BUT NOT MORE THAN 40 PERCENT HYDROGEN PEROXIDE (STABILIZED AS NECESSARY)
column168: UNLOADER WAS UNLOADING A PALLET FROM TRAILER AND STRUCK ONE BOX THAT WAS ON ANOTHER PALLET PUNCTURING BOTH THE BOX AND INNER POLY BOTTLE. THE POLY BOTTLE WAS RUPTURED ON THE SIDE NEAR THE TOP SO VERY LITTLE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED. SPILLED MATERIAL WAS SOAKED UP BY FIBREBOX. DAMAGED POLY BOTTLE WAS PLACED IN A SALVAGE PAIL AWAITING DISPOSITION. FORKLIFT OPERATOR WAS INSTRUCTED TO PAY ATTENTION TO JOB AT HAND AND TO WATCH OTHER FREIGHT WHILE UNLOADING REMAINING BOTTLES IN DAMAGED BOX WHERE PLACE INTO A SMALL SALVAGE CONTAINER AND SHIPPED TO ULTIMATE CONSIGNEE.

column168: UPON UNLOADING FREIGHT AT TERMINAL, UNLOADER NOTICE A PUDDLE UNDER A DRUM. DRUM WAS REMOVED AND FLIPPED OVER AND SPILLED MATERIAL CONTAINED AND CLEANED UP. column168: THE GREAT LAKES CHEMICAL UNIT WAS EASTBOUND ON I-20 NEAR MADISON, GA NEAR MILEMARKER 103 WHEN A DUMP TRUCK MOVING ON THE SHOULDER OF THE INTERSTATE PULLED ONTO THE ROADWAY INTO THE PATH OF OUR UNIT.  GREAT LAKES UNIT STRUCK THE DUMP TRUCK AND THEN OVERTURNED IN THE MEDIAN. THERE WAS  NO SPILL OF HYDROBROMIC ACID BUT THE DUMP TRUCK DRIVER WAS HOSPITALIZED AND THE INTERSTATE SHUTDOWN ON ONE SIDE TO UPRIGHT THE UNIT.  ACCIDENT UNAVOIDABLE DUE TO ACTIONS OF THE DUMP TRUCK DRIVER.  ANY OTHER ACTION BY OUR DRIVER TO AVOID COLLISION WITH THE DUMP TRUCK COULD HAVE RESULTED IN DEATH OR SERIOUS INJURY TO OCCUPANTS OF OTHER VEHICLES.

column168: TRAVELING AT AN ESTIMATED SPEED OF 25 MPH, THE DRIVER LOST CONTROL OF THE DIESEL TRACTOR/CARGO TANK TRAILER, WHEN THE UNIT CONTACTED THE SOFT NARROW SHOULDER OF THE ROAD.  THE ENTIRE TRACTOR/CARGO TANK ROLLED OVER ON ITS RIGHT SIDE AND RUPTURED.  THE RUPTURE WAS SMALL ALLOWING A SMALL TO MODERATE AMOUNT OF PRODUCT TO FLOW FROM THE TANK RATHER THAN ONE LARGE IMMEDIATE LOSS.  A SPILL CONTAINMENT CONTRACTOR WAS IMMEDIATELY HIRED AND WAS ON THE SCENE IN ABOUT 30 MINUTES.  SITE REMEDIATION HAS GONE WELL AND IS EXPECTED TO BE COMPLETED BY THE END OF THE MONTH.  THE SHIPPER NO LONGER ALLOWS ITS LOADED VEHICLES TO TRAVEL ON THIS ROAD.

THIS REQUIRED THE CREW TO BREAK THE TRAIN AT EACH CROSSING TO ALLOW THE FLOW OF MOTORING TRAFFIC. AT APPROXIMATELY 7:30 PM THURSDAY, MAY 25, 2000 NOPB YARDMASTER RECEIVED A CALL FROM SWITCHMAN, R. column168: CORROSIVE LIQUID LEAKER.  SELF CONTAINED.  PROPER PPE WAS WORN. ENTIRE SHIPMENT WAS NEUTRALIZED AND SOLIDIFIED THEN PROCESSED THROUGH THE DMP PROGRAM.
I RESPONDED TO RED BELT IN FULL PPE, USED THE DECISION TREE AND THE RESPONSE SHEET FOR FLAMMABLE LIQUIDS.  I USED CLAY ABSORBENT AND THEN PROCESSED THROUGH THE DMP.
I RESPONDED TO DOOR #6 IN FULL PPE.  I USED THE DECISION TREE AND THE CORROSIVE GUIDE PAGE TO CLEAN UP AND CONTAIN SPILL, NEUTRALIZED THE CHEMICAL AND PROCESSED THROUGH THE DMP
BOX FOUND IN BLUE SECONDARY.  COMPLETE PACKAGE DISPOSED OF THROUGH DMP.  CLEANED AND STORED EQUIPMENT.

WHILE UNLOADING AT THE TERMINAL, ONE 55 GALLON STEEL DRUM WAS DAMAGED.  APPROXIMATELY 15 GALLONS OF FREE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED. APPARENTLY THE DRUM WAS DAMAGED BY A FORKLIFT BLADE.  THE TERMINAL HAZ-MAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEAN UP USING ABSORBENT MATERIALS.  THE CLEAN UP MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO  TWO 35 GALLON FIBER DRUMS WHICH WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL AWAITING DISPOSITION.  THE DAMAGED DRUM WAS PLACED INTO A 65 GALLON STEEL OVER-PACK DRUM AND HELD PENDING SHIPPER CONTACT.  THE BALANCE OF THE SHIPMENT WILL CONTINUE ON TO THE CONSIGNEE.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  AN MSDS WAS RECEIVED FROM THE SHIPPER.

WHILE LOADING, THREE DAMAGED, FIVE GALLON METAL DRUMS WERE DISCOVERED AT THE HALFWAY MARK OF THE TRAILER.  APPROXIMATELY ONE PINT OF FREE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED.  APPARENTLY THE DRUMS WERE DAMAGED DUE TO IMPROPER LOADING.  THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING LEVEL C PROTECTION AND ABSORBENTS.  THE CLEANUP MATERIALS, FREE PRODUCT, AND  AFFECTED SHRINK-WRAP WERE PLACED INTO A TEN GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM.  THE RECOVERY DRUM WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL AWAITING DISPOSITION.  THE THREE DAMAGED DRUMS WERE PLACED INTO THREE SEPARATE, TEN GALLON METAL OVERPACK DRUMS.  THE OVERPACK DRUMS WILL BE FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE ALONG WITH THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED. THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

WHILE UNLOADING, ONE WET CARTON CONTAINING FOUR, ONE GALLON METAL PAILS WAS DISCOVERED AT THE HALFMARK OF THE TRAILER.  UPON FURTHER INVESTIGATION,  IT WAS DETERMINED THAT ONE PAIL WAS DAMAGED AND THREE WERE UNAFFECTED.  APPROXIMATELY 0.25 GALLON OF FREE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED.  APPARENTLY THE DAMAGE WAS DUE TO A PUNCTURE BY A SKID DURING LOADING.  THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING GLOVES, WATER, ABSORBENTS AND A BROOM.  THE CLEANUP MATERIALS, WET CARTON AND DAMAGED CONTAINER WERE PLACED INTO A 55 GALLON METAL RECOVERY DRUM.  THE RECOVERY DRUM WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION.  THE THREE UNAFFECTED PAILS WERE RECOUPED AND ARE BEING HELD AT THE TERMINAL AWAITING INSTRUCTIONS FROM THE SHIPPER.  THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT WAS FORWARDED ON TO THE CONSIGNEE.  THERE WERE NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES REPORTED.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED.

WHILE UNLOADING, FOUR WET CARTONS, EACH CONTAINING THREE, ONE GALLON CONTAINERS WERE FOUND IN THE FRONT QUARTER OF THE TRAILER.  UPON FURTHER INVESTIGATION IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THREE CONTAINERS WERE DAMAGED AND NICE CONTAINERS WERE AFFECTED.  APPROXIMATELY ONE GALLON OF FREE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED.  APPARENTLY THE DAMAGE WAS DUE TO HEAVY FREIGHT LOADED ON TOP.  THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING GLOVES AND ABSORBENT WIPES.  THE CLEANUP MATERIALS, FOUR WET CARTONS AND THREE DAMAGED CONTAINERS WERE PLACED INTO A 35 GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM.  THE RECOVERY DRUM WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION.  THE NINE AFFECTED CONTAINERS WERE CLEANED OFF, RECOUPED AND FORWARDED ON TO THE  CONSIGNEE, ALONG WITH THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT.  THERE WERE NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES REPORTED.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED.

WHILE UNLOADING, A LEAKING 300-POUND CYLINDER WAS DISCOVERED AT THE HALF MARK OF THE TRAILER.  APPROXIMATELY TEN POUNDS OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED.  APPARENTLY THE CYLINDER WAS LEAKING FROM A LOOSE VALVE OR CLOSURE.  THE CONSIGNEE RESPONDED AND TIGHTENED THE VALVE ON THE LEAKING CYLINDER, WHICH WILL BE SENT ON TO THE CONSIGNEE ALONG WITH THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.  STATE AND LOCAL REGULATORY AGENCIES WERE NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT.

AS OF THIS REPORT DATE, WE HAVE NOT RECEIVED ANY INVOICES OF THE LOSS OF PRODUCT, SPILL CLEAN-UP AND 1 OR DISPOSAL. DRIVER WAS TERMINATED FROM EMPLOYMENT.

column58: Basic Material; Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug)
column62: Water Damage; Loose Closure, Component, or Device
column168: THE CUSTOMER COUNTER TRAILER WAS PULLED UP TO DOOR 11 ON THE WEST UNLOAD. PSC WAS NOTIFIED THAT THERE WAS SOMETHING LEAKING FROM INSIDE THE TRAILER BY DISPATCH. UPON UNLOADING THE TRAILER, A PACKAGE WEIGHING 100 LBS. WAS FOUND TO BE LEAKING. AFTER OPENING THE PACKAGE IT WAS DISCOVERED TO BE A WET BATTERY FILLED WITH ACID. THE PACKAGE HAD NO MARKINGS TO LEAD ANYONE TO BELIEVE THIS CONTAINED ANY HAZARDOUS CONTENTS. AN EMBLEM OF A BATTERY HAD BEEN TAPED OVER TO HIDE THE EMBLEM. DIGITAL PICTURES WERE TAKEN AND DISTRIBUTED TO UPLINE MANAGEMENT. WE ARE HOLDING THE CONTENTS. THE ACID FROM THE LEAKING BATTERY DID GET ON AN EMPLOYEE (TIM MISKIMEN). HE WAS ABLE TO WASH IT OFF.
THE PACKAGE WAS DISCOVERED AND IDENTIFIED AT DOOR 24 (FLINT TRAILER). IT WAS TAKEN TO THE PSC AND DMP PROCESSED.

column168: MISSISSIPPI TRANSPORT'S TRACTOR-TRAILER UNIT WAS PROCEEDING EAST ON MINNESOTA TRUNK HIGHWAY 50 AT APPROXIMATELY 0515 A.M.  HIGHWAY 50 IS A TWO-LANE BLACKTOP ROADWAY WITH NARROW SHOULDER AREAS AND, AT THE ACCIDENT SCENE, THE SOUTH SIDE OF THE ROADWAY HAS A DROP-OFF EMBANKMENT.  HEAVY RAIN WAS OCCURRING.  APPROXIMATELY 1/4 MILE WEST OF THE JUNCTION WITH HIGHWAYS US 61 AND MINNESOTA 20 THE UNIT WAS FORCED TO THE SOUTH SHOULDER AREA WHEN AN ON-COMING PASSENGER VEHICLE CAME OVER THE CENTERLINE.  THE TRACTOR REGAINED THE ROADWAY BUT THE HEAVY LOADED TRAILER WAS CAUGHT IN THE SOFT GRAVEL OF THE SHOULDER AND FAILED TO RECOVER THE ROADWAY.  THE TRAILER WENT OVER THE EMBANKMENT AND ROLLED ON TO ITS RIGHT SIDE, FLIPPING THE TRACTOR ON TO ITS RIGHT SIDE.  THE DISCHARGE VALVE LOCATED IN THE RIGHT FRONT SIDE OF THE TRAILER WAS TORN OUT FROM THE INTERNAL TANK SKIN ALLOWING APPROXIMATELY 1200 GALLONS OF HEAVY #6 INDUSTRIAL FUEL OIL TO ESCAPE TO THE ADJOINING FARM FIELD AND DITCH AREA.  FIRE DEPARTMENT UNITS ON THE SCENE CONTAINED THE FLOW OF OIL BY DIKING. CONTRACTED ENVIRONMENTAL CONSULTANTS ARRIVED AND FURTHER SECURED THE AREA.  ALL OIL-CONTAMINATED SOIL HAS BEEN REMOVED AND AREA CLEANED UP TO MEET APPROVAL OF THE MINNESOTA POLLUTION CONTROL AGENCY.

column168: APPROXIMATELY ONE CONTAINER WAS DETERMINED TO HAVE BEEN EMPTY DUE TO APPARENT IMPROPER LOADING (LOAD SHIFTED DURING TRANSPORT AND SEVERAL CASES OF THE MATERIAL SHIFTED CAUSING THE LEAKING CONTAINER TO BE DAMAGED).  IT IS IMPORTANT TO NOTE THAT TWO OTHER CASES OF THE SAME MATERIAL ON THE SAME SHIPMENT WERE DETERMINED TO HAVE BEEN LEAKING WHEN BEAVER HAD INITIALLY RECEIVED THE LOAD ON MAY 26, 2000, FROM CLBT.  THESE CASES WERE RETURNED TO CLBT BY BEAVER.  THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT WAS RELOADED ONTO A TRANSFER UNIT (ULTIMATELY RETURNED TO THE LOADING DOCK FOR OFFLOADING BY BEAVER PERSONNEL (FOR ULTIMATE DELIVERY).  THE 95 GALLON OVERPACK OF CONTAMINATED/LEAKING PRODUCT WAS STAGED AT THE TERMINAL LOADING DOCK FOR FUTURE TRANSPORTATION AND DISPOSAL.  ALL FREE LIQUID WERE ABSORBED AND CONTAINERIZED.  NO FREE LIQUIDS MIGRATED ONTO ANY OTHER SURFACES FROM THE TRAILER BODY (SOME LIQUID WAS ABSORBED ONTO THE UNDERCARRIAGE FRAME OF THE TRAILER.

column168: DRIVER HAD TO MAKE U-TURN TO ENTER FACILITY.  HE WAS WATCHING TRAFFIC, (OBVIOUSLY), TO ENSURE SAFE TURN.  WHEN TRAFFIC CLEARED, DRIVER PROCEEDED TO MAKE TURN AND HIT A POT HOLE WHICH CAUSED THE DRUM DOLLY TO PUNCTURE THE DRUM.  THE HOLE MEASURES 32" DEEP AND SHOULD HAVE BEEN REPAIRED MONTHS AGO!  WHEN THE LEAK WAS DISCOVERED, THE DRIVER PULLED ONTO THE GRASSY MEDIAN TO AVOID ANY CHEMICAL GETTING INTO THE STORM DRAIN.  THE SHIPPER AND BOOTS & COOTS WERE CALLED OUT FOR IMMEDIATE CLEANUP.  HCL WAS NEUTRALIZED AND DRUMMED FOR DISPOSAL.

column168: ONE CASE CONTAINING 4-1 GALLON JUGS OF CORROSIVE LIQUID WAS FOUND TIPPED ON ITS SIDE (BOX WAS WET). TIPPING THE BOX ON ITS SIDE IN TRANSIT, AND 2).  IMPROPER/DEFECTIVE PACKAGING.  THE ENTIRE CASE WAS RECOUPED AND SEALED IN A RECOVERY DRUM.

APPROXIMATELY 1/2 CUP OF THE POWDER HAD LEAKED OUT ONTO TRAILER FLOOR.  TRAILER WAS BROUGHT BACK TO DOCK AND DRUM WAS TAKEN OFF AND SECURED. column168: SAFETY-KLEEN EMPLOYEES WERE IN THE PROCESS OF LOADING A TANK CAR FOR TRANSPORTATION ON THE HIGHWAY WHEN THEY DISCOVERED A GASKET ON THE BOTTOM OF THE CAR WAS DRIPPING.  THE 0.5 OUNCE OF SPILLED PETROLEUM NAPHTHA SOLUTION WAS IMMEDIATELY CLEANED UP WITH ABSORBENT MATERIAL WHILE THE TANK CAR WAS UNLOADED INTO A 20,000 GALLON PORTABLE TANK AND THE GASKET ON THE TANK CAR REPAIRED.  THE SPILL GENERATED APPROXIMATELY 0.5 POUND OF WASTE WHICH WAS TRANSPORTED, ALONG WITH THE ORIGINAL CLEAN MATERIAL, TO THE SAFETY-KLEEN FACILITY AT 16540 SE 130TH IN CLACKAMAS, OR FOR DISPOSAL.  THE RAIL YARD PERSON WAS COUNSELED ON BETTER TANK CAR INSPECTION TO ENSURE NO MORE FUTURE INCIDENTS.

WHILE LOADING A DRUM IN THE BACK OF HIS TRUCK, THE DRIVER DISCOVERED THAT THE BUNG ON A 30 GALLON POLY DRUM WAS LOOSE AND IT SPILLED 0.5 GALLON OF WASTE PHOTO FIXER SOLUTION.  THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED IN THE BACK OF THE TRUCK AND WAS IMMEDIATELY CLEANED UP WITH ABSORBENT MATERIAL.  THE SPILL GENERATED APPROXIMATELY 5 POUNDS OF WASTE WHICH WAS TRANSPORTED, ALONG WITH THE ORIGINAL MATERIAL TO A SAFETY-KLEEN FACILITY AT 960 TURNPIKE ROAD IN CANTON, MA FOR TREATMENT AND DISPOSAL.  THE DRIVER WAS COUNSELED ON PROPER DRUM INSPECTION AND HANDLING PROCEDURES BEFORE TRANSPORTATION TO ENSURE NO MORE FUTURE INCIDENTS.

A SAFETY-KLEEN TRUCK PULLED INTO THE SAFETY-KLEEN FACILITY IN BURLINGTON, NJ AND WHEN THE DOORS OF THE TRAILER WERE OPENED, THEY FOUND IT WAS FULL OF SMOKE.  THE TRAILER WAS PULLED AWAY FROM THE BUILDING AND THE FIRE DEPARTMENT AND AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM WERE ASKED TO COME OUT.  THE MATERIAL SPILLED WAS HYDROFLUORIC ACID AND THE SMOKE WAS CAUSED BY IT REACTING WITH THE PALLET AND THE TRAILER'S FLOOR.  ALL OF THE 5 GALLON CONTAINERS WITH HYDROFLUORIC ACID WERE OVERPACKED INTO 85 GALLON POLY DRUMS AND THE SPILL WAS CLEANED UP WITH ABSORBENT.  THE SPILL PRODUCED APPROXIMATELY 600 POUNDS OF WASTE WHICH WERE TRANSPORTED, ALONG WITH THE ORIGINAL MATERIAL, TO THE SAFETY-KLEEN FACILITY AT 3527 WHISKEY BOTTOM ROAD, IN LAUREL, MD FOR TREATMENT AND DISPOSAL.  THE SAFETY-KLEEN EMPLOYEE RESPONSIBLE FOR THE DRUM PICK-UP WAS COUNSELED ON DRUM AND WASTE INSPECTION TO ENSURE NO MORE FUTURE INCIDENTS.

THE DRIVER WAS AT A CUSTOMER'S SITE WHEN HE DISCOVERED A 55 GALLON STEEL DRUM WAS LEAKING.  FIVE GALLONS OF THE BENZENE SOLUTION SPILLED INTO BACK OF THE TRUCK FROM A PINHOLE LEAK ALONG THE SEAM. THE DRIVER NOTIFIED THE FACILITY MANAGER WHO IMMEDIATELY DISPATCHED AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM WHO OVERPACKED THE 55 GALLON DRUM AND CLEANED THE SPILL WITH ABSORBENT MATERIAL.  THE SPILL GENERATED APPROXIMATELY 50 POUNDS OF WASTE WHICH WAS TRANSPORTED, ALONG WITH THE ORIGINAL MATERIAL, TO THE SAFETY-KLEEN FACILITY AT 3700 LAGRANGE ROAD IN SMITHFIELD, KY TREATMENT AND DISPOSAL.  THE DRIVER WAS COUNSELED ON PROPER DRUM INSPECTION PROCEDURE BEFORE TRANSPORTATION TO ENSURE NO MORE FUTURE INCIDENTS.

THE SPILL WAS DISCOVERED IN THE BACK OF THE TRUCK WHEN IT ARRIVED TO ITS TEN DAY STORAGE FACILITY.  THE DRIVER NOTICED THAT THE SULFURIC ACID AND PETROLEUM DISTILLATE SOLUTION INSIDE THE DRUM WAS LEAKING DOWN THE SIDE.  THE DRIVER WAS MOVING THE DRUM TO DETERMINE THE EXTENT OF THE SPILL WHEN MORE MATERIAL SPILLED OUT OF THE DRUM. WHEN HE REPLACED THE LID OF THE DRUM, THE MATERIAL STOPPED LEAKING OUT.  THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED IN THE BACK OF THE TRUCK AND THE FACILITY MANAGER IMMEDIATELY SENT TO OUT AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE CREW TO CLEAN UP THE SPILL WITH ABSORBENT MATERIAL.  THE SPILL GENERATED APPROXIMATELY 25 POUNDS OF WASTE WHICH WAS TRANSPORTED, ALONG WITH THE ORIGINAL MATERIAL, TO A SAFETY-KLEEN FACILITY AT 300 CANAL STREET IN LAWRENCE, MA FOR TREATMENT AND DISPOSAL.  THE DRIVER WAS COUNSELED ON PROPER INSPECTION PROCEDURE BEFORE LOADING MATERIAL FOR TRANSPORTATION TO ENSURE NO MORE FUTURE INCIDENTS.

column14: 5 MILES NORTH OF NORFOLK ON US
column168: UNIT WAS TRAVELING ON HWY 81 NORTH BOUND 5 MILES NORTH OF NORFOLK 2 LANES MERGED TO ONE LANE. (AT THIS POINT 4 CARS RUSHED TO GET PAST TRUCK) LAST CAR WAS ABOUT 3 TRUCK LENGTHS AHEAD WHEN THE DRIVER NOTICED TWO OF THE CARS TAKE THE RIGHT DITCH SHOULDER. THE 1ST CAR HAD STOPPED TO MAKE A LEFT TURN THE LAST CAR STOPPED BEHIND THE FIRST CAR. (ONE TRUCK WAS COMING IN THE OPPOSITE LANE) THE DRIVER APPLIED BRAKES SO HE WOULD NOT RUN INTO CARS. THE CARS CLEARED AND THE DRIVER DID NOT COME TO A COMPLETE STOP. (DRIVER HAD BACKED OFF FROM HIGHWAY SPEED TO ALLOW CARS TO PASS AT THE MERGE.) DRIVER NOTICED THAT HIS AIR GAUGE SHOWED HIGH-AT THIS POINT HE KNEW THE LOAD SHIFTED. HE FOUND A SPOT TO STOP AND CALLED IN.

A 55 GALLON DRUM OF WASTE TOLUENE WAS IN THE WAREHOUSE OF A TEN DAY STORAGE FACILITY WHERE IT BEGAN TO BULGE AND EVENTUALLY BLEW THE LID OFF. AS A RESULT OF THE RELEASE, 3 GALLONS OF THE MATERIAL SPILLED ONTO THE FLOOR IN A SECONDARY CONTAINMENT AREA. THE SPILL WAS IMMEDIATELY CLEANED UP WITH ABSORBENT MATERIAL AND THE TOLUENE TRANSFERRED INTO A DIFFERENT DRUM. THE SPILL PRODUCED APPROXIMATELY 50 POUNDS OF WASTE WHICH WERE TRANSPORTED ALONG WITH THE ORIGINAL WASTE, TO THE SAFETY-KLEEN FACILITY AT HWY 169 N INDUSTRIAL PARK, IN COFFEYVILLE, KS FOR TREATMENT/DISPOSAL. THE DRIVER RESPONSIBLE FOR THE DRUM PICK-UP COUNSELED ON DRUM AND WASTE INSPECTION PROCEDURES TO ENSURE NO MORE FUTURE INCIDENTS.

column168: THIS PACKAGE SPILLED WHILE IN THE FEDEX WAREHOUSE.  SPILLED MATERIAL GOT ON A VEHICLE, A PLATFORM, AND THE WAREHOUSE FLOOR.  DUE TO A COMBINATION OF THE AMOUNT OF THE SPILL, AND THE FACT THAT THE COMMODITY WAS ACTIVELY DAMAGING THE VEHICLE, IT WAS DECIDED THAT THE SPILL WAS TOO LARGE TO CLEAN UP IN HOUSE.  AN OUTSIDE ENVIRONMENTAL VENDOR WAS CALLED FOR SPILL CLEANUP AND CONTAINMENT.  THEREFORE DETAILS ON THE PACKAGING USED BY THE SHIPPER ARE UNKNOWN.  THE PACKAGE WAS CONTAINED IN SALVAGE DRUM PENDING FINAL DISPOSITION.

AN EMPLOYEE BROUGHT THIS PACKAGE TO THE FEDEX DG SPECIALIST AS HE WAS SUSPICIOUS OF IT AS IT HAD A LABEL WITH A SKULL/CROSSBONES (BUT DESCRIBED AS NOT A HAZARD LABEL FOR TOXIC).  THIS EMPLOYEE RETURNED TO HIS DUTIES DURING THE SORT.  THEN THE DG SPECIALIST NOTICED A SLIGHT ODOR.  HE OBTAINED THE MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET IMMEDIATELY AND FAX'S IT TO ME.  "POISONOUS SOLID N.O.S., UN2811" WAS INDICATED ON THE MSDS.  I HAD JUST INSTRUCTED HIM TO FOLLOW PROTOCOL TO CONTAIN THE PACKAGE IN A FEDEX SALVAGE DRUM AND HOLD  FOR FAA INVESTIGATION FOR UNDECLARED DG. (TOXIC SOLID ORGANIC N.O.S. IS THE EQUIVALENT PROPER SHIPPING NAME IN IATA REGULATIONS FOR THIS 49CFR PROPER SHIPPING NAME.)  THEN I WAS TOLD THEY HAD CALLED THE AMBULANCE FOR THE FIRST EMPLOYEE WHO WASN'T FEELING WELL RATHER THAN DRIVE HIM TO THE HOSPITAL THEMSELVES.  THE AMBULANCE HAD CALLED THE FIRE DEPARTMENT WHO CALLED THE HAZMAT TEAM WHO CALLED COUNTY EPA WHO CALLED STATE EPA.  THESE GROUPS WERE AT THE STATION.  EPA CLEARED THE AREA 400', PERFORMED SOME TESTS, THEN SPOKE WITH ME AND RECOMMENDED THAT WE CALL AN OUTSIDE VENDOR TO HAVE ALL 400' DECONTAMINATED.  AN OUTSIDE VENDOR WAS IMMEDIATELY CALLED IN TO DO SO.  THE EMPLOYEE WAS TREATED AND RELEASED FROM THE HOSPITAL THAT NIGHT FOLLOWING SOME TESTS AND IS FINE.  FAA AGENT CHARLES CLOYD WAS NOTIFIED AND THE PACKAGE WAS HELD PENDING HIS INVESTIGATION.

DURING THE OFF LOADING OF A ULD (UNIT LOAD DEVICE), WHICH IS THE CONTAINER HOLDING THE FREIGHT IN THE FEDEX WAREHOUSE THIS SPILL WAS DISCOVERED.  THERE WERE A TOTAL OF 6 DRUMS SENT.  AT LEAST TWO WERE LEAKING.  DUE TO THE SIZE OF THE SPILL WE CONTRACTED THE SPILL CLEANUP WITH AN OUTSIDE VENDOR.  PROPER SPILL CLEANUP PROCEDURES WERE FOLLOWED AND THE PACKAGES WERE CONTAINED PENDING FINAL DISPOSITION.  THERE WERE NO PACKAGE DISCREPANCIES ASSOCIATED WITH THE SHIPMENT.

column168: SHIPMENT PICKED UP AT CUSTOMER LOCATION.  IN ROUTE TO FEDEX STATION, 1 PACKAGE FELL FROM TRUCK DUE TO INCOMPLETE CLOSURE OF VEHICLE DOOR. AFTER NOTIFICATION BY PASSING MOTORIST, LOCAL POLICE AND FIRE RESPONDED TO CALL.  SHIPPER ULTIMATELY CAME TO SCENE AND CLEANED SITE AND REMOVED ALL SPILLED MATERIAL.  THE OTHER 4 PACKAGES WERE TAKEN TO LOCAL FEDEX STATION FOR INITIAL ACCEPTANCE INSPECTION, BUT WERE REJECTED FOR DOCUMENTATION DISCREPANCIES AND RETURNED TO SHIPPER.  THERE WERE NO INJURIES AND THE ROADWAY REMAINED OPEN DURING THE INCIDENT.

WHILE LOADING, ONE DAMAGED 50 POUND BAG WAS DISCOVERED ON THE DOCK FLOOR.  APPROXIMATELY 16 OUNCES OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED ONTO THE DOCK FLOOR.  APPARENTLY THE DAMAGE TO THE BAG WAS DUE TO A PACKAGING FAILURE.  THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING LEVEL D PROTECTION, A BROOM, AND A DUSTPAN.  THE CLEANUP MATERIALS AND FREE PRODUCT WERE PLACED INTO A 5 GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM.  THE RECOVERY DRUM WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION.  THE DAMAGED BAG WAS RECOUPED INTO A STORAGE BAG AND WILL BE FORWARDED ALONG WITH THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT TO THE CONSIGNEE.  THERE WERE NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES REPORTED.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

A WET CARTON CONTAINING FOUR, ONE-GALLON CONTAINERS WAS DISCOVERED ON THE DOCK.  FURTHER INVESTIGATION DETERMINED THAT ONE CONTAINER WAS LEAKING, AND THREE OF THE CONTAINERS WERE UNAFFECTED. APPROXIMATELY ONE TABLESPOON OF FREE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED. APPARENTLY THE CONTAINER WAS LEAKING FROM A LOOSE LID.  THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING ABSORBENT MATERIALS.  THE WET CARTON, ABSORBENT MATERIALS AND CLEANUP MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO A TEN-GALLON FIBER DRUM.  THE FIBER DRUM WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL AWAITING DISPOSITION.  THE LID ON THE LEAKING CONTAINER WAS TIGHTENED, AND THE CONTAINER WAS REPACKAGED AND SENT ON TO THE CONSIGNEE ALONG WITH THE UNAFFECTED CONTAINERS AND THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

THE RECOVERY DRUM WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION.  NO OTHER FREIGHT WAS  AFFECTED.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

APPARENTLY THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO LOOSE CLOSURES ON THE  CONTAINERS.  THE FREE PRODUCT ABSORBED INTO THE CARTONS. TERMINAL PERSONNEL PERFORMED THE CLEAN-UP USING GLOVES.  THE GLOVES, WET CARTONS, AND THE THREE LEAKING CONTAINERS WERE PLACED INTO A 55-GALLON PLASTIC RECOVERY DRUM.  THE RECOVERY DRUM WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION.  THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT WILL BE FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED. THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

WHILE UNLOADING, A DOCK WORKER DISCOVERED ONE, FIVE GALLON PAIL LEAKING AT THE 3/4 MARK IN THE TRAILER.  APPROXIMATELY ONE CUP OF FREE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED.  UPON FURTHER INVESTIGATION, IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT FOUR PAILS AND THE SHRINK WRAP WERE AFFECTED. APPARENTLY THE LEAKING PAIL WAS DUE TO HEAVY FREIGHT LOADED ON TOP. THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEAN-UP USING LEVEL D PROTECTION ABSORBENT MATERIAL.  THE CLEAN-UP MATERIALS AND SHRINK-WRAP WERE PLACED INTO A 55-GALLON HEAVY DUTY RECOVERY BAG. THE RECOVERY BAG WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION.  THE LEAKING PAIL AND FOUR AFFECTED PAILS WERE WIPED DOWN PER ORDER OF THE SHIPPER AND WILL BE FORWARDED ALONG WITH THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPPER TO THE CONSIGNEE.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED. THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

BOB LOVE WASHED AFFECTED AREA FOR 15 MINUTES WITH SOAP AND WATER AND SENT HIM TO THE HOSPITAL W/ PHIL BOWEN.  * ALL AREAS ON REPORT FILLED OUT UNK ARE BECAUSE FREIGHT IS ON A TRAILER IN THE YARD AND UNABLE TO GET TO FREIGHT DUE TO ITS TOXIC NATURE. DOCKWORKER WAS ADMITTED TO THE HOSPITAL ON 05/26/00 AND KEPT FOR OBSERVATION.  RELEASED 05/28/00- COMPLAINED OF NAUSEA, LIGHT HEADEDNESS.

DOCK MAN DISCOVERED DAMAGED PAIL AS HE WAS UNLOADING FREIGHT FROM THE INBOUND TRAILER.  SOMETHING WAS PUSHED AGAINST THE PAIL AT THE LOADING FACILITY WHICH CRUSHED THE SIDE OF THE PAIL AND TORE A SECTION OF THE METAL WHICH ALLOWED APPROXIMATELY 16 OUNCES OF LIQUID TO ESCAPE.  DAMAGED PAIL TRANSFERRED TO OS&D FOR DISPOSAL BY AN ENVIRONMENTAL CONTRACTOR.  FREIGHT LOADERS MUST EXERCISE GOOD JUDGEMENT AND PROPER LOADING TECHNIQUES TO PREVENT DAMAGE TO HAZARDOUS FREIGHT.

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Inadequate Blocking and Bracing
column168: SHIPMENT RECEIVED IN HARRISBURG, PA AND DURING UNLOADING DOCKWORKER NOTICED A STRONG ODOR AND SAW WET SPOT ON FLOOR OF TRAILER. CHEMTREC WAS NOTIFIED AND ENVIROMENTAL PRODUCTS AND SERVICES WAS CALLED IN TO HANDLE CLEANUP INSPECTION FOUND THAT A DUNNAGE SKID THAT WAS NOT LARGE ENOUGH TO RIDE ON THE 4 UPRITE POST ON EACH CORNER AND THAT DURING MOVEMENT THE FREIGHT THAT WAS STACKED ON THE DUNNAGE SKID HAD CAUSED THE DUNNAGE SKID TO SHIFT AND FALL DOWN BETWEEN THE POST AND HAD KNOCKED THE INNER CAP ON THE SMALL BUNG TO COME OUT AND MATERIAL WAS LOST DUE TO THE BOUNCING OF THE BUNG AS IT TRAVELED FROM DETROIT, MI CLEANUP WAS HANDLED BY ENVIRONMENTAL PRODUCTS AND SERVICES AND DEBRIS WILL BE DISPOSED OF IN ACCORDANCE WITH ALL APPLICABLE LAWS.

DOCKMAN WAS ATTEMPTING TO OFF LOAD A PALLET OF DRUMS WITH A FORKLIFT OFF AN INBOUND TRAILER.  THE DRUMS HAD SHIFTED OFF THE PALLET SOME DURING TRANSIT.  WHEN THE FORKLIFT OPERATOR STARTED TO BACK OUT OF THE TRAILER WITH THE PALLET THE TWO DRUMS BUT THE BACKSIDE STARTED TO FALL OFF.  THE DOCKMAN WAS ABLE TO CATCH ONE OF THE DRUMS BUT THE OTHER ONE FELL AND HIT THE CORNER OF A WOODEN PALLET WHICH WAS LOADED BEHIND THE TWO DRUMS.  THE IMPACT PUNCTURED THE SIDE OF THE DRUMS ALLOWING THE LIQUID CONTENTS TO LEAK OUT ON THE TRAILER FLOOR. AN ENVIRONMENTAL RESPONSE TEAM WAS CALLED IN TO CLEAN UP THE SPILL. THE DOCKMAN RECEIVED CORRECTIVE COUNSELING AND REMEDIAL FORKLIFT TRAINING IN AN EFFORT TO PREVENT FUTURE OCCURRENCES.

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Inadequate Blocking and Bracing
column168: DRIVER REPORTED TO THE CARRIER'S HAZARDOUS MATERIALS TECHNICIAN THAT THEY HAD PICKED UP A SEALED TRUCKLOAD FROM THE SHIPPER. WHILE ENROUTE THE DRIVERS REPORTED A HARDENED MATERIAL FROM AROUND THE NOSE OF THE TRAILER. TRAILER WAS REDIRECTED TO THE CARRIER'S FACILITY FOR INSPECTION. INVESTIGATION REVEALED THAT THE DRUMS WERE LOADED OFF THE NOSE OF THE TRAILER THE DISTANCE OF THE UPPER COUPLER PLATE. LOAD WAS SECURED WITH A FLOOR CHOCK AND A SINGLE LOGISTIC BAR. THE LOAD SHIFTED FORWARD AND ONE DRUM WAS IMPALED BY A NAIL FROM THE WOODED CHOCK. ADDITIONALLY, 2 OTHER DRUMS WERE DAMAGED (DENTED) IN THE SHIFT. THE LEAK FROM THE DAMAGED DRUM WAS SMALL AS THE MATERIAL SOLIDIFIED ITSELF AND SEALED THE LEAK. THE DRUM WAS OVERPACKED BY THE CARRIER AND PLACED BACK ON THE LOAD TO CONTINUE TO GA. SHIPMENT WAS RELOADED ONTO ANOTHER TRAILER TO CONTINUE. THE INBOUND TRAILER WAS PLACED OUT OF SERVICE AND SENT TO A CLEANING FACILITY.

THE DRIVER WAS LOADING HIS TRUCK AT A CUSTOMER'S SITE. WHILE REMOVING A 15 GALLON DRUM FROM A SECONDARY CONTAINMENT PALLET, THE DRUM FELL AND THE LID CAME OFF SPILLING 2 GALLONS OF WASTE TETRACHLOROETHYLENE. THE SPILL WAS IMMEDIATELY CLEANED UP WITH ABSORBENT MATERIAL. THE SPILL GENERATED APPROXIMATELY 20 POUNDS OF WASTE WHICH WAS TRANSPORTED, ALONG WITH THE ORIGINAL WASTE, TO THE SAFETY-KLEEN FACILITY AT 581 MILLIKEN DRIVE, SE IN HEBRON, OH FOR TREATMENT AND DISPOSAL. THE DRIVER WAS COUNSELED ON PROPER DRUM CLOSURE AND HANDLING PROCEDURES TO ENSURE NO MORE FUTURE INCIDENTS.

DRIVER ARRIVED IN THE MORNING AND CHECKED HIS LOAD BEFORE DEPARTING. THE DRIVER FOUND HE HAD PALLET CONTAINING 5 CARBOYS OF SULFURIC ACID. THESE CARBOYS WERE SECURED ON THE PALLET BY SHRINK WRAP. THE DRIVER THEN USED A STRAP TO SECURE THESE CARBOYS. HE ATTACHED THE STRAP TO THE SIDE RAIL ON THE LEFT SIDE OF THE TRAILER APPROXIMATELY 6 INCHES PAST THE FRONT END OF THE PALLET AND THEN SECURED THE OTHER END TO THE RIGHT SIDE OF THE TRAILER. (SEE ATTACHED DIAGRAM). DRIVER THEN DEPARTED THE ROUTE THE DRIVER INITIALLY CHOSE HAD A STREET CLOSED SO HE MADE A "U" TURN. IT IS THOUGHT THAT AT THIS TIME A CARBOY OF SULFURIC BECAME DISLODGED AND STARTED TO ROLL AROUND THE TRAILER. THIS FREE ROLLING CARBOY ROLLED INTO A DRUM AND THE BUNG POPPED OUT- SPILLING SULFURIC ACID. WHEN THE DRIVER SAW A "MIST" FROM THE REAR OF THE TRAILER HE PULLED OFF THE HIGHWAY INTO A FILLING STATION LOT. HE OPENED HIS DRUM AND USED THE ABSORBENT INSIDE TO DIKE A STORM DRAIN. HE THEN OPENED THE TRAILER AND SAW THE OVERTURNED CARBOY OF SULFURIC. HE THEN CALLED HIS  SUPERVISOR.

THE 55 GALLON METAL DRUM WAS OVERPACKED INTO A 85 GALLON SALVAGE DRUM. THE SPILL GENERATED APPROXIMATELY 20 POUNDS OF WASTE WHICH WAS TRANSPORTED, ALONG WITH THE ORIGINAL WASTE, TO THE SAFETY-KLEEN FACILITY AT 633 EAST 138TH STREET IN DOLTON,IL FOR TREATMENT AND DISPOSAL. THE DRIVER WAS COUNSELED ON PROPER DRUM INSPECTION PROCEDURES DONE BEFORE TRANSPORTATION TO ENSURE NO MORE FUTURE INCIDENTS.

DRIVER WAS SOUTH BOUND ON RT 65, ANOTHER  TRUCK WAS BROKE DOWN ON THE BERM.  AT APPROXIMATELY 50-100 FEET FROM THE BROKE DOWN VEHICLE AFTER SLOWING DOWN, THE TOW TRUCK ASSISTING THE DISABLED VEHICLE PULLED OUT IN FRONT OF OUR DRIVER CAUSING HIM TO BRAKE EXCESSIVELY. THIS CAUSED THE CONTAINERS IN THE TRAILER TO MOVE FORWARD AGAINST EACH OTHER, CAUSING DAMAGE TO THE CONTAINERS.  THE DRIVER PULLED OVER AND CHECKED THE VEHICLE TO DISCOVER THE MATERIAL LEAKING.  HE NOTIFIED HIS COMPANY AND WE THEN IMPLEMENTED OUR RESPONSE PLAN AND PROCEDURES.  MATERIAL WAS CONTAINED AND CLEAN-UP WAS COMPLETED.

RUBBER LINER FAILURE, UTLX 12550, MAY 15, 2000, DETROIT DIVISION  AT APPROXIMATELY 1015 HOURS, MONDAY, MAY 15, 1999, AT LIVERNOIS YARD, DETROIT, MICHIGAN, A CONRAIL CARMAN REPORTED PRODUCT UNDER TANK CAR UTLX 12550 RESIDUE LAST CONTAINED FERROUS CHLORIDE SOLUTION. APPROPRIATE NOTIFICATION MADE.  HERITAGE ENVIRONMENTAL ARRIVED AT THE SITE, EXAMINED THE TANK CAR AND DETERMINED THERE WAS A RUBBER LINER FAILURE AT THE BOTTOM FROM THE SKID PLATE.  TANK CAR POWER WASHED FROM INSIDE WITH HOT WATER  AT 3500 PSI AND RINSEATE AND REMAINING SLUDGE REMOVED INTO POLY DRUMS.  ALSO, A DENT WAS NOTED ON LOWER AR HALF UNDERNEATH THE CAR, LOCATED APPROXIMATELY HALF WAY BETWEEN THE CENTER OF THE CAR AND THE INBOARD END OF THE A-END STUB SILL.  FRA MOVEMENT AUTHORITY TO BE OBTAINED FOR MOVEMENT FROM YARD TO UNION TANK CAR COMPANY,  ALTOONA, PA FOR INSPECTION AND REPAIR.
AS THE DRIVER WAS CLEANING SPILLED ASPHALT WITH #2OIL.  2 GALLONS OF THE OIL WAS WASHED INTO CREEK BY THE RAIN.

column168: WHEN THE INNER CONTAINERS LEAKED, THE SPILL CLEANUP SPECIALIST REQUESTED THE MSDS FOR THE LIQUID TO ASSIST IN CLEANUP OF THIS SPILL. THE MSDS GIVEN TO THE FEDEX SPILL CLEANUP SPECIALIST GAVE THIS MATERIAL A FLASHPOINT OF 108 DEGREES FARENHEIT. SINCE THERE WERE DANGEROUS GOODS MARKINGS OR LABELINGS ON THE PACKAGE, THE FAA WAS NOTIFIED OF THIS POSSIBLE UNDECLARED DANGEROUS GOODS SHIPMENT. THERE WAS NO DANGEROUS GOODS PAPERWORK OFFERED TO FEDEX. THIS SHIPMENT IS BEING HELD PENDING FAA INVESTIGATION AND RELEASE.

THIS PACKAGE WAS FOUND TO BE LEAKING WHILE IN THE FEDEX WAREHOUSE. THIS HAD BEEN SENT AS EXCEPTED QUANTITY AND THE UN NUMBER ON THE LABEL COMPLETED BY THE SHIPPER LISTED UN 2811. THIS UN CORRESPONDS TO "TOXIC SOLIDS ORGANIC N.O.S." PROPER SPILL CLEANUP PROCEDURES WERE USED. THERE WAS NO CUSHIONING MATERIAL NOTED BY THE DG/SPILL SPECIALIST. AS THIS IS REQUIRED PER IATA 2.7.8.3 THIS IS BELIEVED TO BE A HIDDEN PACKAGE DISCREPANCY. IN ADDITION, ALTHOUGH THE UN # USED BY THE SHIPPER WAS FOR A SOLID, THE MATERIAL WAS A LIQUID. IN ADDITION, THERE WAS PAPERWORK INSIDE THE SHIPMENT THAT INDICATED THAT THE UN # WAS UN 2810. THIS CORRESPONDS TO "TOXIC LIQUID ORGANIC N.O.S." THIS IS BELIEVED TO BE THE SECOND DISCREPANCY- INCORRECT UN # USED. FINALLY, IF THIS IS INDEED UN 2810 AND IS A LIQUID, THERE WAS NO ABSORBENT MATERIAL WHICH IS REQUIRED FOR LIQUIDS OF EXCEPTED QUANTITY AS OUTLINED IN IATA 2.7.8.3. AS THE PACKAGE IS BELIEVED TO CONTAIN HIDDEN DISCREPANCIES, F.A.A. AGENT PETER ARGEN WAS NOTIFIED. THE PACKAGE WAS HELD PENDING HIS INVESTIGATION.

column168: While loading a return shipment at the consignee location a dock worker discovered wet cartons. The shipment was returned to the terminal for investigation. While unloading, it was discovered that there were thirty-six cartons in the shipment. Upon further investigation it was discovered that twenty-seven cartons and fifty-four pails were damaged.  Approximately 1/2 gallon of free product was released.  Apparently the damage to the pails was due to being crushed in handling.  The Fire Commision  of New Orleans, LA were on the scene and instructed the terminal Hazmat team to place the twenty-seven damaged cartons along with the contents into three, fifty-five gallon plastic recovery drums. The three recovery drums will be held at the terminal for disposition. The remaining nine cartons will be held at the terminal awaiting shipper instructions. No injuries or exposures were reported. The MSDS was requested..

column168: TRUCK DRIVER WAS STOPPED FOR TRAFFIC SIGNAL IN LINE OF TRAFFIC. LIGHT OBSERVED BY DRIVER CHANGED TO GREEN, DRIVER BEGAN TO MOVE AS THE TRAFFIC AT THE LIGHT BEGAN TO MOVE.  HOWEVER TWO CARS JUST AHEAD OF TRUCK REMAINED STOPPED AFTER TRAFFIC MOVED AWAY.  TRUCK DRIVER NOTICED TOO LATE, SLAMMED ON BRAKES BUT HIT CAR IMMEDIATELY AHEAD OF TRUCK.  NO INJURIES NOR WAS EITHER VEHICLE TOWED, BUT THE VIOLENT DOUBLE FORCE ON BRAKE ACTION FOLLOWED BY IMPACT RESULTED IN SCHEDULE 80 PVC FITTING CRACKED JUST OUTSIDE TANK WALL.  THE HIGH-DENSITY CROSSLINKED 1450 GALLON CAPACITY TANK WAS UNDAMAGED, BUT THE BROKEN FITTING ALLOWED SODIUM HYPOCHLORITE BLEACH, UN1791 (10% BY WEIGHT) LADING TO ESCAPE AS DESCRIBED.  VERTEX DISPATCHED A BACKUP TRAILER TO PUMP OFF APPROXIMATELY 100 GALLONS WHICH REMAINED IN THE TRUCK UNSPILLED.  RESIDUE OF 1300 GALLONS WHICH WAS SPILLED ON ROADWAY/SHOULDER FLOWED INTO ROADSIDE DITCH.  VERTEX, AT THE INSTRUCTION OF THE IL EPA EMERGENCY RESPONSE OFFICER WHO SUPERVISED THE RESPONSE OF THIS EVENT, HAD THIS RESIDUE PUMPED INTO ANOTHER VERTEX TRAILER AND REMOVED FROM THE SITE FOR RECLAMATION AND TREATMENT IF NECESSARY.  WHAT WAS REMOVED DID NOT MEET THE STANDARD OF A HAZARDOUS WASTE OR A SOLID WASTE.  CAREFUL EXAMINATION OF THE HAYWARD PVC FITTING (RATED FOR #150 PRESSURE) SHOWED NO EVIDENCE OF MECHANICAL DAMAGE.  APPARENTLY HYDRAULIC PRESSURE COMBINED WITH THE SHOCK OF IMPACT CAUSED THE FITTING TO CRACK.  TIGHTNESS OF STEEL SADDLE SUPPORTS AND WEIGHT OF PRODUCT PREVENTS ANY MOVEMENT OF THIS TANK DURING SHIPMENT.  VERTEX HAS USED HAYWARD PVC FITTINGS ON THESE NON SPECIFICATION TANK AS WELL AS DOT 312 AND NOW, DOT 412 SPECIFICATION RIGS FOR PIPING FOR SODIUM HYPOCHLORITE FOR MANY YEARS AS THE BEST AVAILABLE ALTERNATIVE FOR THE PRODUCT.  THIS PRODUCT IS COMPARATIVELY LOW IN CORROSIVITY ON TISSUE AND IN THE ENVIRONMENT, BUT IS EXTREMELY  CORROSIVE TO METALS.  PLASTIC LINED METAL PIPE GIVES BETTER MECHANICAL STRENGTH, BUT SINCE UNSEEN DAMAGE TO PLASTIC LININGS CAN ALLOW PRODUCT TO ACCESS THE METAL SUBSTRATE WITHOUT WARNING WHICH WILL CAUSE UNCONTROLLED LEAK UNEXPECTEDLY, WELL-PROTECTED PLASTIC PIPING HAS APPEARED TO GIVE THE BEST ALTERNATIVE.  TO PREVENT FUTURE RECURRENCES OF THIS PROBLEM:  SINCE THIS EVENT HAS OCCURRED, VERTEX HAS DECIDED TO INSTALL TITANIUM FITTINGS IN THIS LOCATION, SINCE TITANIUM IS THE ONLY METAL WHICH WILL RESIST THE LADING, OR FRP TANKS WITH MOLDED FITTINGS SINCE FRP MAY GIVE HIGHER CRACK RESISTANCE THAN PVC.

column168: THERE WAS A TRUCK UNLOADING UPON ARRIVAL.  DRIVER CLIMBED TO TOP OF TANK TO CHECK THE OIL LEVEL IN THE CUSTOMERS TANK.  AFTER FIRST TRUCK WAS FINISHED, PROCEDED TO HOOK-UP HOSE AND UNLOAD INTO CUSTOMERS TANK.  AFTER APPROXIMATELY TEN MINUTES OIL STARTED TO FLOW OUT OF THE CUSTOMERS TANK.  FOUND OUT THAT THE CUSTOMERS TANK HAD TWO COMPARTMENTS AND ONLY ONE WAS OPEN.  THE CUSTOMER CAME AND OPENED THE SECOND VALVE AND WE FINISHED UNLOADING INTO HIS TANK.  WE DID NOT HAVE CONTROL OF THE VALVES AND THE CUSTOMER TOLD US HE COULD HOLD THE PRODUCT THAT WE DELIVERED.  TO ENSURE THAT THIS DOESN'T HAPPEN AGAIN  WE WILL ALWAYS CHECK TO MAKE SURE THAT THE TANKS WE UNLOAD INTO HAVE ONLY ONE COMPARTMENT OR MAKE SURE THAT ALL THE VALVES TO ALL COMPARTMENTS ARE OPEN BEFORE WE START THE UNLOADING PROCESS.

column168: ON THE MORNING OF MAY 31, 2000 AT APPROXIMATELY 5:32 AM A RODMAN TRANSPORTATION SERVICE TRUCK WAS TRAVELING SOUTH ON SH121.  AS THE TRUCK APPROACHED THE INTERSECTION OF FM423 IN THE COLONY, TX.  A BLACK FORD RANGER PICK-UP WAS IN THE RIGHT TURN LANE WITH BLINKER ON TO TURN RIGHT ON FR423.  THE PICK-UP TRUCK THEN TURNED LEFT INTO THE LANE OF TRAVEL OF THE RODMAN SERVICE TRUCK.  THE DRIVER OF THE SERVICE TRUCK STEERED LEFT TO AVOID THE PICK-UP.  THE SERVICE TRUCK BEGAN TO SLIDE AND WHEN THE RIGHT. FRONT TIRE OF THE REAR TANDEM BLEW OUT, THE SERVICE TRUCK OVERTURNED.  THE BLACK FORD PICK-UP WAS NOT INVOLVED AND LEFT THE SCENE.  APPROXIMATELY 2400 GALLON OF DIESEL FUEL WAS SPILLED ONTO THE ROAD SURFACE AND GRASSY AREAS ON BOTH SIDES OF THE ROAD.  A HAZ-MAT CLEANUP COMPANY (DISPOSAL SERVICES) WAS CALLED AND THE AREA WAS EVACUATED.  THE TEXAS NATURAL RESOURCES CONSERVATION COMMISSION WAS CONTACTED AND A REPORT WILL BE FILED WITH THEM  THE TEXAS DEPARTMENT OF TRANSPORTATION WAS NOTIFIED AND HAD ENGINEERING PERSONNEL AT THE SCENE.  THE CLEAN-UP WAS PERFORMED WITH APPROVALS OF TNRCC AND TX-DOT.  THE DIESEL FUEL REACHED ANY WATER SOURCE OR STORM DRAINS NOR WERE THERE ANY SUCH AREA IN CLOSE PROXIMITY TO THE SPILL

column168: DURING TRANSPORTATION TO OUR HOUSTON TERMINAL, A NAIL PUNCTURED THE BOTTOM OF THE DRUM CAUSING SOME PRODUCT TO LEAK INTO THE TRAILER. THE DRUM AND CLEANUP MATERIAL HAS BEEN PLACED IN A RECOVERY DRUM AWAITING DISPOSITION FROM THE SHIPPER.

RESPONDED TO PD-9.  USING DECISION AND WEARING PPE PROCESSED SPILLED MATERIAL ACCORDING TO RESPONSE SHEET FOR CORROSIVES.  SOLIDIFIED AND NEUTRALIZED ALL MATERIAL AND PROCESSED IT THROUGH THE DAMAGED MATERIAL PROGRAM.

(A-Q) TANK CAR INVOLVED IN THE UNION PACIFIC RAILROAD TRAIN DERAILMENT AT EUNICE, LOUISANA, 5/27/2000. REAR PART OF TRAIN THAT DID NOT DERAIL.  ON 5/29/2000, THIS REAR PORTION OF THE TRAIN WAS BEING MOVED TO THE BASILE SIDING WHEN THE TANK CAR WAS DISCOVERED TO BE LEAKING FROM THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE. STATE, PARISH AND FEDERAL AUTHORITIES WERE NOTIFIED.  UNION PACIFIC MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION, MIKE KELLY, ALONG WITH OTHER RESPONSE PERSONNEL INCLUDING DOW CHEMICAL AND THE LOUISANA STATE POLICE EVENTUALLY FLARED. THE REMAINING VAPORS AND PURGED THE CAR WITH NITROGEN.  THE DEFECTIVE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE WAS REPLACED ON THE CAR.  SUBSEQUENT SHOP INSPECTION OF THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE INDICATED THAT THE VALVE STEM WAS BOWED, POSSIBLY AS THE RESULT OF THE FORCE FROM THE DERAILMENT OF 5/27/00.

TANK ARRIVED AT CARRIER'S FACILITY FROM THE SHIPPER, WAS UNLOADED FROM THE PICK UP TRAILER AND SET ON THE DOCK. SOME TIME LATER A DOCK PERSON OBSERVED A SMALL POOL OF LIQUID UNDER IT. AT FIRST INSPECTION IT APPEARED THAT THE LEAK WAS UNDER A FORK POCKET. DOCK SUPERVISOR, WITH THE CONCURRENCE OF CARRIER'S ON CALL HAZMAT PERSON DETERMINED TO SET THE TANK OUTSIDE OF THEIR BUILDING WITH A CATCH BASIN AND SPILL PADS UNDER THE LEAK AREA. A REPORT WAS MADE TO THE SHIPPER VIA THEIR EMERGENCY RESPONSE TELEPHONE NUMBER INDICATING THAT THE PROBLEM WAS AS DESCRIBED. IT WAS AGREED THAT THE MATTER WAS SUFFICIENTLY CONTROLLED AND THAT ABSENT ANY CHANGE, NO FURTHER ACTION WOULD BE NEEDED UNTIL MORNING. SHIPPER'S REPRESENTATIVE SAID THAT HE WOULD ARRANGE FOR A PRODUCT TRANSFER THEN. WHEN THE TANK WAS ACTUALLY MOVED TO THE OUTSIDE OF THE BUILDING, IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT THE LEAK WAS NOT WHERE IT WAS ORIGINALLY THOUGHT TO BE. RATHER, IT WAS COMING FROM A CRACK IN A WELD AT TEMPORARY PATCH. ONCE DONE, THEY ORDERED THE TANK RETURNED TO THE FACILITY TO HAVE ITS CONTENTS TRANSFERRED TO A NEW TANK. SPILLAGE OF PRODUCT ONTO THE DOCK WAS MINIMAL AND WAS CLEANED UP BY DOCK PERSONNEL.

column168: DURING UNLOADING AT THE CARRIER'S FACILITY OF A TRAILER INBOUND FROM THE SHIPPER, THE DOCK WORKER OBSERVED LEAKAGE AND FOAMING FROM THE DISCHARGE OF ONE TANK. HE SET THE TANK IN A SECURE AREA AND NOTIFIED HIS SUPERVISOR WHO IN TURN NOTIFIED THE CARRIER'S HAZMAT DEPARTMENT. HAZMAT CONTACTED THE SHIPPER WHO GAVE ADVICE FOR TEMPORARY MEASURES, THEN SENT PERSONNEL AND A NEW TANK TO THE CARRIER'S FACILITY. SHIPPER PERSONNEL EFFECTED A TRANSFER OF THE PRODUCT TO THE NEW TANK,  DECONTAMINATED THE CARRIER'S DOCK AND REMOVED THE DEFECTIVE TANK FROM THE PREMISES. THE SHIPMENT WAS THEN ALLOWED TO CONTINUE TO ITS DESTINATION WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT.

WHILE DROPPING FUEL AT CUSTOMER LOCATION, THE OVERFILL PROTECTION SYSTEM CAME ON CAUSING PRESSURE IN THE HOSE AND FITTING AREA.  THIS CAUSED THE OVERTIGHT CONNECTION TO COME OFF RESULTING IN A SPILL OF 15 GALLONS ON CONCRETE.  THIS WAS CLEANED UP USING ABSORBENTS. THE CAP(S) WERE SECURED. THE CARTON WAS WET BUT OTHERWISE UNDAMAGED. THE PACKAGE WAS REPACKED FOR RETURN TO SHIPPER.

CTN WAS PLACED IN OVERPACK CONTAINER AND WILL BE DISPOSED OF BY ENVIRONMENTAL PRODUCTS AND SERVICES IN ACCORDANCE WILL ALL APPLICABLE LAWS.

MISSION DRIVER WAS UNLOADING AT CUSTOMER LOCATION. THE TRAILER DEVELOPED A LEAK DURING UNLOADING. THERE WAS 1 ONCE OF RESIN SOLUTION SPILLED. THE DRIVER CLEANED UP THE SPILL. THE TRAILER WAS NOT IN FOR REPAIRS. THE DRIVER IS NOT AT FAULT.

DESTINATION WAS NEW STATION UNDER CONSTRUCTION. CONTRACTORS INSTALLED UNDERGROUND STORAGE TANK BACKWARDS. CONTRACTOR CALLED FOR FILL TO HOLD TANKS DOWN. CONTRACTOR ORDERED 5500 GALS TO BE PUT IN A 5000 GAL TANK. DRIVER REALIZED PROBLEM WHEN FUEL SPRAYED OUT VENT PIPE. DRIVER SHUT DOWN PRODUCT FLOW & DIVERTED REST OF LOAD. SPILL CLEANED UP BY OMNI ENVIRONMENTAL  & REPORTED TO MPCA NO FAILURE OF CARGO TANK OR DRIVER.
AFTER FILLING THE GENERATOR TANK, FUEL BELCHED BACK OUT OF THE FILL, STAINING THE ASPHALT.

column168: DONNED PPE, AND SCBA, FOLLOWED DECISION TREE, AND RESPONSE SHEET FOR KEEP AWAY FROM FOOD, AND DESPOSED ENTIRE CONTENTS THROUGH DMP.

DONNED PPE. FOUND A STAINED FLAMMABLE LIQUID BOX ON THE NORTH SORT AISLEY, DECISION TREE + FLAMMABLE LIQUID RESPONSE SHEET WHERE USED IN THE PROPER HANDLING OF PACKAGE, THE ENTIRE CONTENTS WERE SOLIDIFIED AND DISPOSED OF THROUGH DMP.

A LOADER NOTICED A WET PACKAGE LABELED WITH A DOT 6.1 DIAMOND LABEL AND 8- PART FORM ON BROWN BELT.  SUPERVISOR TOM MCCOY (A DESIGNATED RESPONDER) RESPONDED TO IT AND BROUGHT IT TO THE PSC AREA. DESIGNATED RESPONDER COMPLETING THIS FORM CONSULTED UPS DECISION TREE + DOT 6.1 RESPONSE SHEET + DONNED FULL PPE.  ALL LIQUID WAS ABSORBED USING CLAY BASED ABSORBENT. ALL CONTAMINATED MATERIALS WERE DISPOSED OF THRU UPS DMP PROCEDURES.

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Water Damage
column168: A SORTER NOTICED A LEAKING PACKAGE LABELED DOT CORROSIVE ON THE BACK NORTH SORT AISLE.  ACCESS TO THE AREA WAS RESTRICTED AND A DESIGNATED RESPONDER WAS NOTIFIED.  UPS DECISION TREE + CORROSIVE RESPONSE SHEET WERE CONSULTED + FULL PPE WITH SCBA WAS DONNED. LIQUID HAD A PHO.  SODIUM BICARBONATE WAS ADDED UNTIL LIQUID HAD A PH7.  CLAY BASED ABSORBENT WAS USED TO SOLIDIFY ALL LIQUID.  ALL CONTAMINATED MATERIALS WERE DISPOSED OF THRU UPS DMP PROCEDURES.

column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Water Damage
column168: A SUPERVISOR NOTICED A LEAKING PACKAGE LABELED DOT CORROSIVE, ACCESS TO THE AREA WAS RESTRICTED AND A DESIGNATED RESPONDER WAS NOTIFIED. THE UPS DECISION TREE AND CORROSIVE LIQUID RESPONSE SHEET WERE CONSULTED.  FULL PPE WAS DONNED.  THE LIQUID HAD A BEGINNING PH OF O. SODIUM BICARBONATE WAS USED TO NEUTRALIZE THE LIQUID AND BRING IT TO A NEUTRAL 6 READING. CLAY BASED ABSORBANT WAS USED TO ABSORB ALL LIQUID. ALL CONTAMINATED MATERIALS WERE DISPOSED OF THRU UPS DMP PROCEDURES.
DONNED PPE, REFERRED TO DECISION TREE & FLAMMABLE LIQUID RESPONSE SHEET.  CONTAMERIZED SPILL AND RETURNED TO S/C AREA.  DISPOSED OF DAMAGED BOTTLE AND CONTAMINATED CARDBOARD THRU DMP.

column168: FOR AN INTERFACILITY MOVE THE SHIPMENT HAD BEEN LOADED IN THE FRONT OF THE TRAILER.  ON ARRIVAL AT THE DESTINATION FACILITY, ONE PALLET HAD TURNED OVER.  A NUMBER OF PAILS HAD FALLEN OFF ONTO THE FLOOR. TWO OF THE PAILS HAD CRACKED AND FAILED AT THE TOPS.  ABSORBENT MATERIAL WAS USED TO CLEAN UP THE SPILLAGE IN THE TRAILER.  THE PAILS AND THE ABSORBENTS WERE SET ASIDE FOR SHIPPER'S INSTRUCTIONS FOR DISPOSAL.

UPON DELIVERING FREIGHT AT HIS FIRST STOP, THE DRIVER NOTICED A FUNNY SMELL ON THE TRAILER.  UPON INVESTIGATION OF THE ODOR, HE FOUND TWO DRUMS STRAPPED TO THE WALL OF THE TRAILER ON THE TAIL END. ONE OF THE DRUMS HAD CRYSTALS FORMED AROUND A NAIL HOLE IN THE TOP. THE OTHER DRUM HAD CRYSTALS FORMED AROUND THE BOTTOM CHIME.  NO SPILLAGE WAS IN THE TRAILER AND THE DRUMS WERE NOT LEAKING.  SINCE THE DRUMS WERE DELIVERING TO A CLOSE BY LOCATION IN THE SAME TOWN CARRIER'S HAZMAT TECHNICIAN GAVE INSTRUCTIONS TO VENTILLATE THE TRAILER BEFORE MAKING THE NEXT DELIVERY AND CONTINUE TO THE CONSIGNEE.  IN THE MEANTIME, HAZMAT CONTACTED THE SHIPPER TO DISCUSS THE NATURE OF THE PRODUCT AND ACCEPTANCE BY THE CONSIGNEE.  THE SHIPPER'S REPRESENTATIVE INDICATED THAT ONCE THIS PRODUCT IS EXPOSED TO MOISTURE(IN THE AIR), THE PRODUCT IS NO GOOD BECAUSE IT STARTS TO REACT AND CRYSTALLIZE.  HE GAVE INSTRUCTIONS TO PLACE THE DRUMS IN METAL OVERPACKS FOR RETURN TO THEM.

column62: Impact with Sharp or Protruding Object (e.g., nails)
column168: UPON ARRIVAL AT THE CONSIGNEE, THERE WAS A STRONG ODOR RADIATING FROM THE TRAILER.  CONSIGNEE INSTRUCTED THE DRIVER TO REMOVE THE TRAILER FROM THE DOCK AND TAKE IT TO A QUARANTINE AREA AND LIMITED ENTRY TO THEIR ON SITE HAZMAT TEAM ONLY.  THE HAZMAT TEAM REMOVED THE SHIPMENT OF DRUMS FROM THE TRAILER REVIEWING EACH FOR LEAKAGE. THE CAME UPON A PALLET OF DRUMS IN WHICH ONE OF THE SLATS OF THE PALLET HAD BEEN BROKEN AND WAS JAMMED INTO THE PALLET OF DRUMS SITTING DIRECTLY IN FRONT OF IT (TOWARDS THE HEAD OF THE TRAILER). THE BOARD THAT JAMMED INTO THE DRUM PUNCTURING IT CAUSED AN APPROXIMATE 1 GALLON LOSS OF PRODUCT.  THE PRODUCT SPILLED ON THE TRAILER FLOOR.  SOME OF THE PRODUCT SOAKED INTO THE WOOD FLOOR AND THE REMAINDER WAS ABSORBED BY SPEEDY DRY THAT THE HAZMAT TEAM PUT DOWN.  THE HAZMAT TEAM SWEPT UP THE CONTAMINATED SPEEDY DRY AND WILL HANDLE DISPOSAL.  THE CONSIGNEE ACCEPTED THE DRUM WITH A DAMAGE NOTATION ON THE DELIVERY RECEIPT.

NINETY-SIX PAILS OF A 100 PAIL SHIPMENT WERE PALLETIZED.  THE PALLETS WERE LOADED INTO THE CARRIER'S TRAILER AGAINST ITS WALLS, LEAVING A LONGITUDINAL GAP AT THE CENTERLINE.  THE FOUR LOOSE PAILS WERE ON THE TRAILER FLOOR, IN THE GAP BETWEEN THE PALLETS. DURING TRANSIT THE PAILS RUBBED AGAINST THE PALLETS, EVENTUALLY ABRADING HOLES IN THREE OF THE FOUR.  THE DAMAGED PAILS WERE REMOVED FROM THE LOAD AND OVERPACKED TO AWAIT THE SHIPPER'S INSTRUCTIONS.  DRIVER WAS GIVEN EXTRA INSTRUCTIONS ON LOADING.

column58: Cylinder Neck or Shoulder; Cylinder Sidewall - Other
column168: DRIVER CALLED FROM HIS FIRST STOP, SHIPMENT IS 6 RACKS OF EMPTY CYLINDERS AND 10 LOOSE CYLINDERS WHICH WERE STRAPPED TO THE TRAILER WALL WITH TWO STRAPS.  THE BOTTOM STRAP HAD COME LOOSE FROM ITS LOGISTIC TRACK, ALLOWING THE CYLINDERS TO FALL TO THE FLOOR.  THERE IS AN ODOR OF AMMONIA IN THE TRAILER.  CARRIER'S HAZMAT TECHNICIAN INSTRUCTED THE DRIVER TO BRING THE TRAILER BACK TO ITS NEARBY FACILITY FOR INSPECTION AND CORRECTION OF THE PROBLEM.  WHEN THE TRAILER ARRIVED A TECHNICIAN MADE ENTRY AND DISCOVERED ONE CYLINDER WITH ITS VALVE NOT SECURELY CLOSED.  HE TIGHTENED THE VALVE AND THE ODOR DISSIPATED.  AFTER BEING ADVISED OF THE INCIDENT BY THE SHIPPER, A REPRESENTATIVE OF CONSIGNEE CALLED THE CARRIER FOR A BRIEFING.  HE OFFERED TO SEND PERSONNEL TO THE CARRIER'S FACILITY TO MAKE ENTRY IF NEEDED.  AFTER LEARNING THAT THE INCIDENT WAS UNDER CONTROL, HE ASKED THAT THE SHIPMENT BE DELIVERED.  SHIPMENT DELIVERED THE FOLLOWING DAY WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT.
column172: Seamless steel, made of definitely prescribed steels

column42: PAINT INCLUDING PAINT, LACQUER, ENAMEL, STAIN, SHELLAC SOLUTIONS, VARNISH, POLISH, LIQUID FILLER AND LIQUID LACQUER BASE
column168: ONE DRUM BEGAN LEAKING AFTER IT WAS TAKEN OFF OF THE TRAILER AND SET ONTO THE CONSIGNEE'S DOCK.  THERE WAS NO SPILLED MATERIAL ON THE TRAILER FLOOR, BUT ONCE THE DRUM WAS ON THEIR DOCK AND THE LOOSE SHRINK WRAP WAS REMOVED FROM IT AND ITS PALLET, LEAKAGE FROM A HOLE IN THE DRUM SHELL BEGAN.  IT APPEARS THAT THE CONSIGNEE'S DRUM PICK POKED A HOLE IN THE DRUM DURING UNLOADING.  CONSIGNEE DENIED CAUSING THE DAMAGE.  THEY CLAIM THAT IT WAS ALREADY DAMAGED, BUT THE SHRINK WRAP HELD THE SPILLAGE UNTIL THE SHRINK WRAP WAS REMOVED.  SHIPPER AGREED TO TAKE THE DRUM BACK FOR INSPECTION.  CARRIER HAD IT OVERPACKED FOR THE RETURN TRIP.

DRIVER HAD SMELLED A BAD ODOR WHILE DELIVERING AT A STOP.  HE REPORTED THERE WAS A TOTE IN THE NOSE AND THE FLOOR AROUND IT WAS WET. DRIVER WAS SENT TO A NEARBY CARTAGE CARRIER'S FACILITY.  THE CARRIER RETAINED A CLEAN UP CONTRACTOR TO RESPOND TO THE INCIDENT. CONTRACTOR ARRIVED AND FOUND THE TOTE WAS LEAKING FROM A 1"-1.5' " SLICE AT THE CORNOR OF THE TOTE.  DAMAGE MAY HAVE BEEN CAUSED DURING LOADING OR IF FREIGHT WAS STACKED ATOP THE TOTE.  THE CONTRACTOR WAS ABLE TO PATCH THE SLICE WIT A RUBBER AND EPOXY GLUE SEAL.  TRAILER FLOOR WAS NEUTRALIZED OF THE SPILLED ACID AND THE FREIGHT WAS RELOADED AND TAKEN TO THE CARRIER'S FACILITY.  UPON ARRIVING THERE PATCH ON THE TOTE BEGAN LEAKING AGAIN.  THE TOTE WAS QUARANTINED WHILE ARRANGEMENTS WERE MADE WITH A LOCAL CONTRACTOR TO TRANSFER THE CONTENTS OF THE TOTE TO DRUMS.  ONCE DONE, THE DRUMS OF PRODUCT AND THE EMPTY TOTE WERE RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT.

column42: COMPOUND, CLEANING, LIQUID (CONTAINING PHOSPHORIC ACID, ACETIC ACID, SODIUM HYDROXIDE OR POTASSIUM HYDROXIDE)
column168: SHIPMENT HAD BEEN LOADED ONTO A TRAILER FOR DELIVERY.  AT SOME TIME AFTER LOADING LIQUID WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING FROM THE TRAILER.  DOCK PERSONNEL TRANSFERRED THE LOAD TO ANOTHER TRAILER.  WHILE DOING SO THEY FOUND ONE DRUM SQUEEZED IN AND CRACKED AT THE BOTTOM RADIUS AS A RESULT. THERE WAS NO DUNNAGE BEHIND THOSE DRUMS TO PREVENT PUSHING FROM FREIGHT BEHIND THEM.  DRUM WAS PLACED ON ITS SIDE ON A PALLET AND PUT INTO OS&D.  THE DRUM IS TO BE PUT INTO A SALVAGE DRUM AND RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER.  DOCK PERSONNEL DILUTED THE MATERIAL AND RINSED THE TRAILER.

ONE DRUM WAS LEAKING FROM A CRACK IN A DENT IN ITS LOWER ROLLING HOOP.  THE ENTIRE SHIPMENT APPEARS TO HAVE BEEN JAMMED IN.  THE LOGISTIC BAR BEHIND  IT WAS STILL QUITE TIGHT.  CONSIGNEE WOULD NOT ACCEPT IT BUT THEIR DOCK SUPERVISOR PATCHED THE CRACK WITH PIG PUTTY, THEN SET THE DRUM ONTO ITS SIDE AND SECURED IT TO A PALLET FOR RETURN TO THE CARRIER'S FACILITY.

column42: PRINTING INK, FLAMMABLE OR PRINTING INK RELATED MATERIAL (INCLUDING PRINTING INK THINNING OR REDUCING COMPOUND), FLAMMABLE
column168: AT TIME OF DELIVERY ONE RECONDITIONED DRUM WAS LEAKING FROM ITS BOTTOM HEAD AT THE CHIME.  THE DRUM WAS ON THE FLOOR, BUT THERE WAS NOTHING IN THE FLOOR TO HAVE CAUSED ANY DAMAGE.  THE CONSIGNEE ACCEPTED THE DRUM AND CLEANED THE TRAILER FLOOR FOR THE DRIVER.

column42: PAINT INCLUDING PAINT, LACQUER, ENAMEL, STAIN, SHELLAC SOLUTIONS, VARNISH, POLISH, LIQUID FILLER AND LIQUID LACQUER BASE
column168: DRUM ARRIVED ON INBOUND SHUTTLE TRAILER FROM ANOTHER FACILITY OF THE CARRIER.  IT WAS LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM OF THE SHELL AT THE CHIME AREA.  THERE WAS NOTHING IN THE TRAILER FLOOR TO HAVE CAUSED ANY DAMAGE.  IT IS BELIEVED TO BE A PACKAGING FAILURE.

DRIVER ARRIVED AT THE CONSIGNEE, AND FOUND ONE PAIL WITH ITS LID POPPED OPEN SLIGHTLY. THIS PAIL WAS LOCATED ON A PALLET OF 3 DRUMS AND ONE OTHER PAIL. THE PALLET APPEARS TO BE SHIPPER SHRINK WRAPPED (TIGHTLY), THE PAIL THAT WAS LEAKING WAS LOCATED ON TOP OF THE OTHER PAIL ON THIS PAIL. NO DAMAGED COULD BE SEEN TO THE PAIL'S LID WHICH WOULD HAVE CAUSED THE LID TO OPEN. A MINIMAL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT HAD SPLASHED ONTO THE OTHER PAIL AND DRUMS. DRIVER ALSO SAID THAT THE SHIPMENT WAS ALSO 3 PAILS SHORT.

A DOCK EMPLOYEE WAS BEGINNING TO REMOVE FREIGHT FROM AN INBOUND TRAILER WHEN HE SMELLED A STRONG ODOR RADIATING FROM THE TRAILER. HE SAW A WET SPOT AROUND A DRUM SITTING ON THE FLOOR OF THE TRAILER NEAR THE TAIL END. THE MANIFEST PRINT-OUT DID NOT SHOW WHAT THE MATERIAL WAS AND THE DRUMS WERE NOT MARKED WITH HAZARD LABELS. THE EMPLOYEE BROUGHT HIS SUPERVISOR TO THE TRAILER TO SHOW HIM THE DRUM. THE SUPERVISOR IMMEDIATELY CONTACTED THE CARRIER'S HAZARDOUS MATERIALS DEPARTMENT, AND DID NOT ALLOW ANYONE TO ENTER THE TRAILER. A HAZARDOUS MATERIALS TECHNICIAN USING A RESPIRATOR INSPECTED THE TRAILER AND SWEPT UP THE OIL USED ON THE SPILL. AN EXAMINATION OF THE DRUMS SHOWS THE DRUMS WERE RECONDITIONED AND THAT THE LEAKER WAS POOR CONDITION. THE DRUM WAS DENTED AND LEAKING FROM THE VERTICAL SEAM ON THE SIDE OF THE DRUM. IT IS ALSO APPARENT THAT THE DRUMS WERE FILLED BY THE SHIPPER IN THIS CONDITION- AS THE DENTED AREA ON THE DRUM WAS REPAINTED. THE MATERIAL IN THE DRUM IS VERY HEAVY, 700 LBS. THE DRUMS WERE ALSO NOT MANUFACTURED TO HANDLE A MATERIAL OF THIS WEIGHT. THIS INFO WAS GATHERED FROM THE PACKAGING SPEC. HAZMAT PATCHED THE DRUM AND IT WAS OVERPACKED AND LEFT IN THE SPILL SECTION. LESS THAN 1/2 GALLON WAS LOST IN THE TRAILER. DUE TO THE NATURE OF THE MATERIAL, IT QUICKLY EVAPORATED FROM THE WOODEN FLOOR. THE TRAILER WAS PLACED IN THE YARD TO VENTILATE ANY REMAINING FUMES IN THE TRAILER. NO FURTHER CLEAN-UP WAS NECESSARY. THE HAZARDOUS MATERIALS DEPARTMENT CONTACTED CHEMTREC TO OBTAIN A MSDS. DURING A RETURN CALL FROM THE SHIPPER CARRIER'S TECHNICIAN RELAYED THE DETAILS OF THE EXPOSURE INCIDENT AND PACKAGING ISSUES PERTAINING TO THE CONTAINER LABELING AND RECONDITIONED DRUMS. A REPRESENTATIVE OF THE SHIPPER PICKED-UP THE TWO (2) DRUMS AND RETURNED THEM TO THE SHIPPER'S FACILITY. THERE THEY WERE RE-PACKED INTO PROPER NEW CONTAINERS, MARKED AND LABELED, AND RETURNED TO THE CARRIER FOR DELIVERY TO THE CONSIGNEE.

DRIVER HAD DELIVERED TO ANOTHER STOP WHICH WAS NEARBY. THE SHIPMENT THAT WAS DELIVERED THERE HAD BEEN LOADED ON TOP OF THE DAMAGED SHIPMENT. WHEN UNLOADING AT THE CONSIGNEE, TWO CARTONS THAT HAD BEEN ON TOP OF THE DAMAGED SHIPMENT WERE FOUND TO HAVE BEEN CRUSHED BY THE  FREIGHT THAT HAD BEEN ON TOP OF IT. ONE JUG IN EACH OF THE CARTONS HAD BEEN CRUSHED TO THE POINT THAT THEY LEAKED PART OF THEIR CONTENTS ONTO OTHER CARTONS OF THE SHIPMENT. CONSIGNEE ACCEPTED ALL WITH A DAMAGE NOTATION. LEAKAGE WAS CONFINED TO THE CARTONS AND THE PALLET. NONE WAS ON THE TRAILER FLOOR.

TWO BAGS WERE STRUCK BY A FORKLIFT AND BROKEN OPEN. DOCK PERSONNEL SWEPT UP THE SPILLAGE AND PUT THE DAMAGED BAGS INTO A TEMPORARY CONTAINER ALONG WITH THE SWEEPINGS. THE UNDAMAGED PORTION OF THE SHIPMENT WAS DELIVERED TO THE CONSIGNEE. AT THE REQUEST OF THE SHIPPER THE BALANCE, INCLUDING THE SWEEPINGS, WAS RETURNED.

column168: AT TIME OF DELIVERY ONE CAN WAS FOUND TO HAVE BEEN CRUSHED AND WAS LEAKING. THE CARTON THAT IT WAS IN APPEARED TO HAVE BEEN JAMMED IN DURING LOADING FOR DELIVERY. CONSIGNEE WOULD NOT ACCEPT THE CAN. THE DRIVER ACQUIRED A PLASTIC PAIL TO PUT IT IN FOR RETURN TO THE CARRIER'S FACILITY.

column62: Impact with Sharp or Protruding Object (e.g., nails)
column168: DURING STRIPPING OF INBOUND SHUTTLE VEHICLE FROM ANOTHER FACILITY OF THE CARRIER, ABOUT TWO GALLONS OF MATERIAL WAS FOUND ON THE TRAILER FLOOR. IT WAS COMING FROM A SCRAPE ON THE BOTTOM. THE DRUM APPEARS TO HAVE BEEN DRAGGED ACROSS A NAIL OR OTHER SHARP OBJECT DURING HANDLING AT THE ORIGINATING FACILITY. DOCK PERSONNEL OVERPACKED THE DRUM, PUT OIL DRY ONTO THE SPILLAGE, SWEPT IT UP AND PUT IT INTO A PAIL. CARRIER'S HAZMAT SPECIALIST CONTACTED SHIPPER. THE SHIPPER REQUESTS THAT THE OIL DRY AND ANY OTHER CLEAN UP MATERIALS BE PUT INTO THE SAME DRUM AND RETURNED TO THE SHIPPING LOCATION. THEY WILL HANDLE DISPOSAL OF ANY WASTES.

UPON ARRIVAL OF THE INBOUND PICKUP VEHICLE AT THE CARRIER FACILITY, A DOCK WORKER BEGAN OFF-LOADING THESE PALLETS OF BAGS. HE FOUND SOME BAGS TORN DUE TO HAVING BEEN HANGING OVER THE EDGES OF THE PALLETS. DUE TO THE NATURE OF THE MATERIAL BEING A POWDER MATERIAL AND A POISON (6.1 PG III), CARRIER'S HAZMAT SPECIALIST REQUESTED THAT THE PALLETS BE BROKEN DOWN, THE BAGS PROPERLY FITTED TO EACH PALLET AND THE TORN BAGS PUT ON A SEPARATE PALLET TO AWAIT DISPOSITION FROM THE SHIPPER. HAZMAT TECHNICIAN SUPERVISED AND INSTRUCTED THE DOCK WORKERS ON PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT TO BE WORN AND SAFETY MEASURES TO BE FOLLOWED WHILE HANDLING THIS MATERIAL. THE BAGS WERE RE-PALLETIZED WITH NO BAGS OVERHANGING. AFTER BEING SECURED FROM FURTHER LEAKAGE, THE DAMAGED BAGS WERE PLACED ONTO ONE ADDITIONAL PALLET. THE ENTIRE SHIPMENT, INCLUDING THE DAMAGED BAGS, WAS DELIVERED WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT. THE INCIDENT WAS REPORTED TO THE SHIPPER AND A LENGTH DISCUSSION HELD WITH THEM WITH RESPECT TO THE PALLETIZING OF BAGS.

WHILE A PALLET OF BAGS OF H/M WERE STAGED ON THE CARRIER'S DOCK, ONE BAG WAS STRUCK BY AN UNIDENTIFIED PASSING FORK LIFT. SPILLED MATERIAL WAS CLEANED UP AND PLACED INTO AN OVERPACK CONTAINER ALONG WITH THE DAMAGE BAG, AND RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER.

column168: WHILE IN TRANSIT THE CARRIER'S DRIVER WAS NOTIFIED OF LEAKING MATERIAL FROM THE REAR OF THE TRAILER. UPON ARRIVAL THERE, ONE TOTE WAS FOUND TO BE LEAKING FROM AROUND ITS MANWAY COVER.  THE TOTE ONLY LEAKS WHEN IT IS IN TRANSIT. column168: DRIVER STATES THAT HE WAS MAKING DELIVERY OF A RUSH SHIPMENT ON A SUNDAY MORNING.  THE CONSIGNEE OF THE SHIPMENT HAD AGREED TO MOVE ANY FREIGHT NECESSARY (THREE OTHER SHIPMENTS) IN ORDER TO ACCESS THEIRS.  A SINGLE DRUM SHIPMENT OF H/M WAS AT THE TAIL OF THE TRAILER, STRAPPED TO THE WALL. DRIVER STATES THAT HE WAS IN THE TRAILER WHILE THE UNLOADING AND RELOADING WAS TAKING PLACE, BUT HE DID NOT OBSERVE ANY ACCIDENTAL CONTACT TAKE PLACE BETWEEN THEIR FORK LIFT AND ANY OTHER FREIGHT.  WHEN HE ARRIVED AT HIS FIRST STOP THE NEXT MORNING, HE SAW ABOUT A QUART OR LESS OF MATERIAL ON THE FLOOR, COMING FROM A CRACK IN THE SIDE OF THE SINGLE DRUM.  IT APPEARED TO HAVE BEEN GRAZED BY A FORK.  THE DRIVER WIPED UP THE LEAKAGE AND THE SIDE OF THE DRUM, PLACED A SEALANT OVER THE CRACK AND CONTINUED TO THE CONSIGNEE.  THEY WOULD NOT ACCEPT THE DRUM, BUT ASSISTED THE DRIVER TO CLEAN UP THE SPILLAGE FROM THE DRUM AND THE TRAILER FLOOR, AND SECURED IT FOR RETURN TO THE SHIPPER.

column168: CARRIER'S DRIVER WAS MAKING DELIVERIES OF A SHIPMENT OF INK CONSISTING OF 48 DRUMS ON PALLETS AND A SINGLE DRUM ON THE TRAILER FLOOR, NOT ON A PALLET.  WHEN HE ARRIVED AT THE CONSIGNEE, THERE WAS A PUDDLE OF WHITE INK ON THE TRAILER FLOOR AS WELL AS A TRAIL OF INK ON THE CONSIGNEE'S ENTRANCE AND PARKING LOT.  THE TRAIL WAS IDENTIFIED AS COMING FROM THE SINGLE DRUM THAT HAD BEEN LOADED ON THE TRAILER FLOOR.  THE DRIVER STATED THAT THERE WAS NO LEAKAGE EVIDENT AT HIS PREVIOUS STOP.  AT FIRST, IT WAS THOUGHT TO BE A CRACK IN THE BOTTOM OF THE DRUM.  WHEN THE DRUM WAS TURNED UPSIDE DOWN, THEY FOUND WHAT THEY BELIEVED TO BE A NAIL HOLE.  THE DRIVER USED MATERIALS FROM HIS SPILL KIT TO ABSORB THE SPILLAGE ON THE FLOOR.  AFTER A DISCUSSION OF THE SITUATION WITH THE CONSIGNEE'S RECEIVING SUPERVISOR, AND THEN THE OPERATIONS MANAGER, THE CARRIER'S HAZARDOUS MATERIALS SPECIALIST AGREED TO SEND A CONTRACTOR TO EFFECT A CLEANUP.  A CONTRACTOR WAS RETAINED AND SENT TO THE SITE FOR THAT PURPOSE.  THE CONTRACTOR ALSO PLACED THE DAMAGED DRUM INTO A SALVAGE DRUM FOR ITS ULTIMATE RETURN TO THE SHIPPER. THE CARRIER SUBSEQUENTLY RECEIVED A CALL FROM A REPRESENTATIVE OF THE SHIPPER WHO INDICATED THAT ADDITIONAL WORK WOULD BE NECESSARY TO RESTORE THE PREMISES.  THE CONTRACTOR WAS AGAIN RETAINED TO GO BACK TO THE LOCATION AND PERFORM THE ADDITIONAL WORK.
