column168: AT HIS FIRST STOP, THE DRIVER DISCOVERED WHITE PRODUCT LEAKING FROM THE TRAILER.  AT THIS POINT IN TIME, THE CUSTOMER WAS NOT OPEN AND THE LEAK WAS SLOW.  THE CARRIER'S HAZMAT TECHNICIAN INSTRUCTED THE DRIVER TO PLACE SPILL ABSORBENT PADS UNDERNEATH THE TRAILER, AND TO REMAIN THERE.  THE CARRIER RETAINED A SPILL CONTRACTOR TO RESPOND TO THE INCIDENT TO OVERPACK THE LEAKING DRUM(S), CLEAN-UP THE SPILLAGE IN THE TRAILER AND ON THE GROUND. IN THE MEANTIME, THE CUSTOMER'S FACILITY OPENED FOR BUSINESS.  EMPLOYEES THERE ASSISTED THE DRIVER IN REMOVING FREIGHT FROM THE TRAILER TO FIND THE LEAKING CONTAINER.  TWO PALLETS IN FROM THE TAIL OF THE TRAILER, A 55-GALLON STEEL DRUM OF PRINTING INK WAS FOUND LEAKING FROM BOTTOM.   UPON CLOSER INVESTIGATION, A CRACK WAS FOUND IN ITS BOTTOM HEAD.  THE CUSTOMER HAD A SALVAGE DRUM WHICH THEY MADE AVAILABLE FOR THE LEAKING DRUM. HOWEVER, THEY DID NOT HAVE ANY ABSORBENT TYPE MATERIAL TO CLEAN-UP THE SPILLAGE IN THE TRAILER.  WHEN THE CONTRACTOR ARRIVED AND BEGAN WORK, THEY FOUND A SECOND DRUM ON ANOTHER PALLET WITH A SMALL PUDDLE UNDER IT AND FRESH PAINT ON THE BOTTOM RIM.  CARRIER AUTHORIZED PLACING IT INTO A SALVAGE DRUM AS WELL.  A REPRESENTATIVE OF THE RHODE ISLAND DEPT. ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGEMENT APPEARED ON LOCATION TO OBSERVE THE PROCEEDINGS. THE REPRESENTATIVE STAYED FOR ABOUT FIVE MINUTES AND LEFT.  HE IS REPORTED TO HAVE BEEN SATISFIED WITH THE PROGRESS OF THE JOB.  BOTH LEAKING DRUMS WERE PLACED INTO SALVAGE DRUMS AND OFFERED TO THEIR CONSIGNEE.  THEY WERE REFUSED AND TAKEN TO THE CARRIER'S FACILITY FOR EVENTUAL RETURN TO THEIR SHIPPER.

column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: ON MAY 27, 2000 OUR TRANSPORT DRIVER HAD JUST LEFT THE MARATHON TERMINAL IN DETROIT, AND WAS HEADING NORTH ON I-75 WITH A FULL LOAD OF GASOLINE (13,400 GALLONS). IT HAD JUST STARTED TO RAIN AS HE APPROACHED THE OFF-RAMP TO 375. WHEN THE DRIVER ENTERED THE RAMP, THE TRANSPORT LOST TRACTION AND SLID LEFT OFF THE TRAVELED PORTION OF THE HIGHWAY, AND UP AGAINST THE CONCRETE RETAINING BARRIER. THE TRANSPORT CONTINUED WITH ITS WHEELS SCRAPING THE BARRIER. SHORTLY INTO THE TURN, THE TRAILER HIT ONE OF THE PILLARS OF AN OVER-PASS, RUPTURING THE LEFT FRONT CORNER OF THE TRAILER. THE RESULTING GASOLINE SPILL IGNITED, COMPLETELY ENGULFING THE TRAILER AND POWER UNIT. THE DRIVER WAS HOSPITALIZED AND AS A RESULT OF THE BURNS RECEIVED, PASSED AWAY THE FOLLOWING DAY. THE DRIVER WAS OBVIOUSLY GOING TOO FAST FOR THE WET ROAD CONDITIONS. HOWEVER, IF THE PILLARS OF THE OVERPASS WERE POSITIONED BEHIND, INSTEAD OF JUTTING OUT FROM, THE CONCRETE BARRIER, THE TRAILER WOULD NOT HAVE MADE CONTACT WITH PILLAR, AND VERY LIKELY COULD HAVE AVOIDED THIS VERY SERIOUS INCIDENT.

column168: *SEE ATTACHED COPY OF KENTUCKY DIVISION FOR AIR QUALITY INSPECTION REPORT. OUR DRIVER ARRIVED AT THE RICH OIL STATION IN SUMMIT, KY. HE PROCEEDED TO LOCATE THE DROPS AND CHECK THE TANK CHARTS TO MAKE SURE THE PRODUCT WOULD HOLD. HE HOOKED UP THE VAPOR RECOVERY LINE FIRST, THEN HOOKED UP THE FITTINGS AND HOSES TO UNLOAD THE PRODUCT. AS THE UNLEADED HOSE WAS EMPTYING, THE DRIVER NOTICED GAS SPRAYING UP FROM THE DRAIN BUCKET. HE SHUT DOWN THE LOADING HEAD, CALLED OUR TERMINAL MANAGER AND WAS ADVISED TO CALL THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT. WHEN THE FIRE DEPARTMENT ARRIVED THEY PUT DOWN A BOOM AROUND  A DRAIN. IT WAS DETERMINED THAT DEBRIS WAS HOLDING OPEN THE BASKET DRAIN VALVE AND THIS ALLOWED THE GASOLINE TO SHOOT OUT. THE SPILL OCCURRED BECAUSE THE STATION HAD REPAIR WORK DONE ON THE DROP TUBE AND THEY FAILED TO MAKE SURE THE DRAIN BUCKET VALVE WAS WORKING PROPERLY. OUR EQUIPMENT DID NOT FAIL IN ANY WAY AND OUR DRIVER RESPONDED AS TRAINED.

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: CARRIER'S VEHICLE WAS INVOLVED IN A CRASH IN WHICH IT STRUCK A REPORTEDLY ABANDONED VEHICLE. THE TRACTOR AND THE TRAILER SEPARATED. THE TRAILER WAS UPSIDE DOWN AT THE SIDE OF THE ROADWAY. THE TRACTOR WAS ALSO UPSIDE DOWN, IN WOODED AREA NEXT TO THE ROADWAY. FIRE, POLICE, EMS AND FIRE DEPT. HAZARDOUS MATERIALS UNITS RESPONDED. THE SOUTHBOUND LANES OF I-85 WERE CLOSED. THE DRIVER AND A PASSENGER WERE TRANSPORTED TO A TRAUMA CENTER VIA HELICOPTER. AS IT WAS KNOWN FROM THE OUTSET THAT CLEAN UP ACTIVITIES WOULD BE NEEDED, THE CARRIER RETAINED A CONTRACTOR TO PROCEED TO THE SITE AND HANDLE THAT ASPECT OF THE INCIDENT. INCLUDING THE  HAZARDOUS MATERIALS LISTED ABOVE AND THE CONTENTS OF THE TRACTOR'S FUEL TANKS, APPROXIMATELY 500 GALLONS OF LIQUIDS WERE SPILLED. THE FIRE DEPARTMENTS CONSTRUCTED BERMS AND CONTAINMENTS AROUND ALL AREAS WHERE LIQUIDS WERE LEAKING AND /OR COLLECTING. AFTER THE INJURED PERSONS WERE REMOVED AND THE HIGHWAY CLEARED, I-85 WAS REOPENED. IT HAD BEEN CLOSED FOR APPROXIMATELY TWO HOURS. CARRIER'S CONTRACTOR REMOVED ALL SPILLED MATERIALS , EXCAVATING WHEN NECCESSARY TO DECONTAMINATE THE  SITE. ALL CONTAINMENTS WERE PLACED INTO APPROPRIATE CONTAINERS FOR DISPOSAL. THE VEHICLES WERE REMOVED LATER IN THE DAY. THE CONTRACTOR REMAINED ON/RETURNED TO THE SITE UNTIL IT WAS RESTORED TO ITS ORIGINAL CONDITION.

CALLED FIRE DEPT. 911 AND OLIVER COUNTY EMERGENCY MGR. ALSO HEALTH DEPT WERE ON THE SCENE CLEANED UP AREA & RE SEEDED GRASS. TANK & TRAILER JUNKED.

DURING TRANSPORT THE DRUM BEGAN TO LEAK & WAS DETECTED BY CARDINAL'S DRIVER DURING ROUTINE INSPECTION.  CONTAMINATE CONTROL INC WAS CALLED TO THE SCENE TO SECURE THE MATERIAL & CLEAN UP THE LEAK.  THE STATE OF S.C. REQUESTED THE TRAILER BE REMOVED FROM THE REST AREA.  IT WAS TAKEN TO CARDINAL'S N.C. OFFICE & DECONTAMINATION TOOK PLACE. column168: WHILE UNLOADING #2 DIESEL FUEL FROM TANK TRUCK TO BULK TANK, CONNECTION CAME APART ON FITTING.  APPROX. 80-90 GALLONS OF FUEL WAS SPILLED ONTO PARKING LOT.  FUEL WAS PICKED UP USING ABSORBENT MATERIAL AND PLACED INTO 2 - 55 GAL DRUMS FOR DISPOSAL.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: DUE TO A LOADING ACCIDENT, THE TANKER TRUCK LEAKED DIESEL FUEL FROM AN UNDERGROUND STORAGE TANK.  THIS INCIDENT SPILLED 150 GALLONS OF FUEL ON THE PARKING LOT AND INTO THE STORM DRAIN.  THE CHARLOTTE FIRE DEPT AND MECKLENBURG COUNTY ENVIRONMENTAL PROTECTION WERE NOTIFIED.  THE FIRE DEPT PERSONNEL CONTAINED THE SPILL.  THE SPILL AREA IN THE PARKING LOT WAS 60 FEET BY 50 FEET.  THE WENT INTO A STORM DRAIN AND RAN THROUGH THE PIPE 150 YARDS TO AN OUTFALL IN A SMALL CREEK.  SPECTRUM ENVIRONMENTAL WAS CALLED TO THE SCENE TO BEGIN CLEAN UP OPERATIONS.  THE CONTAMINATED OIL DRY MATERIAL WAS SWEPT OFF THE PARKING LOT INTO 55 GALLON DRUMS.  THREE 10 FOOT BOOMS WERE PLACED IN THE OUT FALL OF THE STORM DRAIN SYSTEM.  THE CONTAINMENT BOOM STATIONS WERE SET UP TO CONTAIN AND CAPTURE THE FUEL.  THE FIRE DEPT FLUSHED 500 GALLONS, THEN 200 GALLONS OF WATER DOWN THE STORM DRAIN. SPECTRUM CAPTURED THE FUEL AT THE DOWN GRADIENT LOCATION AND PUMPED UP 957 GALLONS OF WATER AND FUEL OF WHICH 100 GALLONS WAS DIESEL FUEL.  THE BOOM STATIONS WERE LEFT IN PLACE, FOR FOUR DAYS, TO CAPTURE ANY REMAINING FUEL. THIS IS DONE BY SPREADING ABSORBENT PADS IN FRONT OF THE BOOMS TO SOAK UP THE FUEL.  AFTER THE PADS BECOME SATURATED WITH FUEL, THEY ARE REMOVED WITH NETS TO A DISPOSAL DRUM.  FRESH ABSORBENT MATERIALS ARE REPLACED TO THE BOOM STATIONS.  ON 5-5-00, THE BOOM STATIONS WERE CLEANED UP AND THEN REMOVED.  A TOTAL OF 5 DRUMS OF CONTAMINATED OIL DRY MATERIAL, BOOMS AND PADS, FOR DISPOSAL, WILL BE TAKEN TO BFI/CMS LANDFILL.  THE DIESEL/WATER WAS TAKEN TO HAZMAT, INC FOR DISPOSAL (SEE MANIFEST).

column168: ON MAY 1, 2000 OUR VEHICLE WAS INVOLVED IN A TRAFFIC ACCIDENT WHILE IN ROUTE TOO CANUTE, OK.  THE OTHER VEHICLE INVOLVED WAS TRAVELING EASTBOUND IN THE WESTBOUND LANE OF I-40.  AT APPROXIMATELY 0430 TO 0500, AT MM 123, THE VEHICLE TRAVELING EAST STRUCK OUR CARGO TANKER ON THE DRIVER SIDE IN FRONT OF REAR AXLES.  OUR DRIVER MADE EVERY ATTEMPT TO AVOID THE ACCIDENT, HOWEVER, IMPACT OCCURRED CAUSING CARGO TANKER TO RUPTURE, WHICH IN TURN, CAUSED A HAZARDOUS SPILL ALONG WITH FIRE.  OUR DRIVER WAS NOT INJURED BUT THE DRIVER OF THE OTHER VEHICLE WAS A FATALITY.  IMMEDIATE ACTION WAS TAKEN BY OUR DRIVER AND COMPANY TO ENSURE THE SAFETY OF THE PUBLIC AND THE ENVIRONMENT BY CONTAINING THE SPILL AND PROVIDING FOR THE CLEANUP.

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: THE DRIVER WAS EAST ON KY-146 (LAGRANGE ROAD) ENTERING A LEFT HAND CURVE. HE WAS APPROXIMATELY 142FT. INTO THE CURVE WHEN THE RIGHT SIDE WHEELS DROPPED OFF THE EDGE OF THE PAVEMENT. AT THIS TIME THE DRIVER TURNED THE WHEEL HARD TO HIS LEFT CAUSING THE VEHICLE TO GO OUT OF CONTROL AND OVERTURN. POLICE AND EMERGENCY RESCUE PERSONNEL RESPONDED TO THE SCENE. OUR EMERGENCY RESPONSE VENDOR REPORTED TO THE SCENE TO BEGIN THE CLEAN UP. THIS ACCIDENT IS DISCUSSED AT ALL DRIVER SAFETY MEETINGS AND WE URGE OUR DRIVERS TO USE CAUTION WHEN DRIVING.

DRIVER WAS RADIOED BY ANOTHER TRUCK THAT IT APPEARED THAT HE WAS LEAKING SOMETHING.  OUR DRIVER PULLED OVER TO CHECK HIS LOAD.  THE DRIVER NOTICED A LEAKING DRUM NEAR THE REAR OF THE VAN, WHICH APPEARED TO BE CAUSED BY THE RUBBING OF DRUMS AND RESULTING IN PIN HOLE LEAK IN ONE OF THE DRUMS.  THE ESTIMATED VOLUME OF LEAKAGE WAS NO MORE THAN 20 GALLONS.  THE DRIVER CALLED FOR SUPPORT AND THEN TRIED TO STOP THE MINOR LEAK.  THE DRIVER WAS OVERCOME BY FUMES.  SUPPORT PERSONNEL, MOBILE COUNTY HAZMAT AND UNITED STATES ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES, ARRIVED AND THE DRUM WAS OVERPACKED AND THE VAN WAS CLEANED.  THE TRUCK WAS IMPOUNDED UNTIL THE LOAD COULD BE SECURED..  THE LOAD WAS SECURED UNDER THE OBSERVATION OF A DOT INSPECTOR AND THE DRIVER CONTINUED ON THE EL DORADO FACILITY.

TRUCK DRIVER OBSERVED FUMES COMING FROM VAN AND NOTIFIED FIRE DEPARTMENT. FIRE DEPARTMENT RESPONDED AND OPENED VAN WHERE LEAKING TOTE WAS DISCOVERED. LEAK WAS CONTAINED AND FIRST STRIKE ENVIRONMENTAL (COB #108932) CONTACTED FOR CLEANUP - CONTAMINATED SOIL CLEANUP COMPLETE ON 5-26-00.
THE BULK TRUCK WAS OVER FILLED IN LOADING PROCESS.

column168: I WAS CALLED TO RESPOND TO A LEAKING PACKAGE WITH MY PPE ON.  UPON INSPECTION I FOUND THE PACKAGE WAS NOT WET, BUT HAD PREVIOUSLY BEEN WET AND DRIED.  THE UNLOADER SENT THE PACKAGE OUT TO BE SORTED BEFORE NOTICING IT HAD PROBABLY BEEN LEAKING AND THEN HAD A CHANCE TO DRY.  THERE WAS ONE LOOSE CAP ON THE 8 BOTTLES. NO REMARKS

APPROXIMATELY FIVE GALLONS OF FREE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED INTO THE TRAILER AND ONTO THE ASPHALT OF THE YARD.  THE DAMAGE TO THE PAIL WAS CAUSED BY PUNCTURE DURING LOADING.  THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING GLOVES, BOOTIES, ABSORBENTS, ABSORBENT PADS, A DUSTPAN AND BRUSH.  THE CLEANUP MATERIALS, PADS, AND ABSORBENTS WERE PLACED INTO A FIVE GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM.  THE RECOVERY DRUM WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION.  THE DAMAGED PAIL WAS PLACED INTO THE TERMINAL'S WASTE RECEPTACLE.  THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT WAS FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED.

THIS REPORT IS BEING FILED IN COMPLIANCE WITH 49CFR THIS INCIDENT IS OR MAYBE SUBJECT TO FURTHER INVESTIGATION BY AMERICAN AIRLINES. THIS REPORT IS NOT TO BE CONSTRUCTED AS AN OFFICIAL DETERMINATION OF THE CAUSE OF THE INCIDENT.  A BAG, MISTAGGED FOR GRU WAS DISCOVERED TO CONTAIN PARTY SUPPLIES WHICH INCLUDED 2 BAGS OF PARTY POPPERS, 12 EACH.  THE FLIGHT THE BAG WAS TAGGED FOR WAS CALLED BACK TO THE GATE AFTER REPORTING, SO THAT THE REMAINING BAGS BELONGING TO PASSENGER COULD BE CHECKED.  AT THIS POINT THE ACTUAL PASSENGER WAS IDENTIFIED, BAGS AND PASSENGER WERE TRAVELING ON FLT 303 TO CCS.  NO ADDITIONAL REGULATED MATERIALS WERE FOUND.  THE LOCAL FAA INSPECTED AND RELEASED THE BAG CONTAINING THE REGULATED MATERIAL.  THE "PARTY POPPERS" WERE SAFELY DISCHARGED AND PASSENGER ALLOWED TO TRAVEL.  NO SPILLAGE OR RELEASE INVOLVED, REPORT BEING FILE DUE TO GROUND INTERRUPT OF FLT 929 TO GRU ON  05/01/00.

column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 9:30AM ON 5/20/2000 WHILE NATE MCDOWELL WAS LOADING A TANK TRUCK OF POTASH FROM RAILCAR GATX49570 THE RAILCAR BEGAN TO LEAK ABOVE THE VALVE.  NATE IMMEDIATELY STOPPED PUMPING MATERIAL AND RELIEVED ALL AIR PRESSURE ON THE RAILCAR, HOWEVER, THE RAILCAR CONTINUED TO LEAK MATERIAL.  AT APPROXIMATELY 9:45AM I BRIAN ALEXANDER RECEIVED THE PHONE CALL FROM NATE ABOUT THE PROBLEM.  WHEN I ARRIVED ON SITE TO ASSESS THE PROBLEM THE RAILCAR WAS STILL LEAKING SLOWLY FROM ABOVE THE OUTLET VALVE.  AFTER SPEAKING WITH NATE AND EVALUATING THE SITUATION IT WAS DETERMINED THAT ALL LOST MATERIAL WAS CONTAINED WITHIN PRIMARY CONTAINMENT AND THAT THE RAILCAR NEEDED TO BE EMPTIED IMMEDIATELY.  SO WE PUMPED THE MATERIAL VIA A PORTABLE PUMP TO OUR STORAGE TANK FOR CAUSTIC POTASH.  THE COLLECTED SPILLED MATERIAL WAS DILUTED AND PUMPED TO OUR PH NEUTRALIZATION SYSTEM, ADJUSTED AND THEN DISCHARGED VIA OUR POTW PERMIT.

THE "ROAD SERVICE REPORT" RECEIVED FROM EST STATES THAT @ 11:40 PM ON MAY, 2000, DAN HOGAN (APCI DRIVER) WAS INSTRUCTED BY EST TO STAY ON THE SIDE OF THE ROAD UNTIL THE PRESSURE STABILIZES.  GASEOUS NITROGEN FROM THE LIQUID NITROGEN TRAILER WAS VENTING, DETECTED BY THE DRIVER AS HE WAS TRAVELING UPHILL.  ONCE THE TRAILER VENTING CEASES, THE DRIVER WILL CONTINUE ON HIS WAY. APPARENTLY, DUE TO THE EXCESS VENTING, "CLOUDS" BLEW ACROSS THE INTERSTATE.

UPON INSPECTION OF THE BAGGAGE,  RAMP EMPLOYEES DISCOVERED A SINGLE CAN OF AEROSOL PAINT DULLER WHICH WAS LOCATED INSIDE OF A TOOLBOX.  THE TOOLBOX WAS CONTAINED(WITH ANOTHER TOOLBOX AND A ROLLING DOLLY) WITHIN A LARGE DUFFEL BAG.  THE TOOLBOXES WERE SEARCHED FOR ADDITIONAL DANGEROUS GOODS AND ALLOWED TO BE TRANSPORTED WITH THE CUSTOMER TO DALLAS LOVE FIELD, THE CUSTOMER'S FINAL DESTINATION.  THE FAA WAS NOTIFIED VIA THE REGIONAL CENTER IN FORT WORTH AND THE EVIDENCE OF THE SHIPMENT WAS MAINTAINED IN HOU PENDING THE FAA'S INVESTIGATION.

column168: THIS REPORT IS BEING FILED IN COMPLIANCE WITH 49 CFR.  THIS INCIDENT IS OR MAY BE SUBJECT TO FURTHER INVESTIGATION BY AMERICAN AIRLINES. THIS REPORT IS NOT TO BE CONSTRUED AS AN OFFICIAL DETERMINATION OF THE CAUSE OF THE INCIDENT.  A WET BAG WAS DISCOVERED IN THE OUTBOUND BAGROOM.  PASSENGER ERESIA IDENTIFIED THAT THE CONTENTS OF THE BAG INCLUDED AMMONIA.  UPON SEARCH OF THE BAG NO ORIGINAL CONTAINERS WERE FOUND.  ESTIMATED TO BE 32 OUNCES SPILLED FROM SECONDARY CONTAINER. column168: UPON ARRIVAL OF TRAILER 206561,  MAY 31,  2000, FROM DES MOINES TRAILER DOOR WAS OPENED TO ATTEMPT TO BEGIN WORKING INBOUND TRAILER. UPON OPENING DOOR TRAILER WAS FILLED WITH FUMES AND INK WAS SPREAD THRU LAST HALF AREA OF TRAILER.  CHECKED BILLS THIS WAS WHITE PRINTING INK.  TRAILER WAS PULLED TO YARD WITH DOOR OPENED SO THAT FUMES COULD EVAPORATE.  ONCE FUMES EVAPORATED,  TRAILER WAS PULLED BACK TO DOCK AND A PORTION OF FREIGHT WAS PULLED OFF TRAILER. LUCKILY, ALL FREIGHT WAS ON SKIDS SO THERE WAS NO DAMAGE OR CONTAMINATION TO OTHER FREIGHT.  SAFETY WAS CALLED IN HOLLAND. ALSO,  SCOTT COUNTY ENVIROMENTAL SERVICES WERE CALLED AND CAME OUT FOR THE CLEAN-UP.  WAS IN CONTACT WITH SHIPPER AND CHEMTREC... LINDA JOLLY

column168: ON MAY 22, 2000, MR. FRANCOIS TRAVELED FROM MDW TO RDU ON SWAA FLIGHT NUMBER 814. HE CHECKED SEVERAL ITEMS TWO OF WHICH WERE TOOL BOXES. A STRONG PAINT ODOR WAS NOTICED IN THE CUSTOMER CLAIM AREA, AND UPON INSPECTION OF ONE OF THE TOOL BOXES AN AEROSOL CAN OF PAINT FINISH WAS PUNCTURED AND LEAKED ONTO THE TOOL BOX. RAMP PERSONNEL DID NOT NOTICE ANY SIGNS OF LEAKAGE OR ODOR ON THE AIRCRAFT OR DURING THE DOWN LOAD PROCESS. SOUTHWEST NOTIFIED THE LOCAL FAA CASFU UPON DISCOVERING THE INCIDENT. MR. FRANCOIS WAS QUESTIONED ABOUT THE TOOL BOXES AND THEIR CONTENTS UPON CHECK-IN AT MDW, BUT HE INDICATED THAT THERE WERE ONLY TOOLS INSIDE. HIS STATEMENT REVEALS THAT HE SIMPLY FORGOT THAT THE TOOLBOX CONTAINED THE AEROSOL CANS.

column168: DEAN C. COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS CONTACTED BY RMCC REPORTING A LEAKING TANK CAR  AT BAKERSFIELD. DEVELOPED THE ABOVE TANK HAD ARRIVED BAKERSFIELD AT 9AM, AND WAS NOTED TO HAVE LEAKED BY THE MECHANICAL DEPARTMENT FORCES WHILE THEY WERE INSPECTING THE TRAIN FOR DEPARTURE. THE CAR WAS SENT TO THE RIP TRACK WHERE IT COULD BE ISOLATED PENDING INSPECTION. MANAGER COOPER DROVE TO THE BAKERSFIELD YARD AND MET WITH THE BAKERSFIELD FIRE DEPARTMENT, WHO WAS STANDING BY ON SCENE. INSPECTION DEVELOPED THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK TO BE FROM A BURST FRANGIBLE DISC IN THE SAFETY VENT. THE SAFETY VENT, A STANDARD GATX TRI-VENT MOUNTED ON TOP OF THE MANWAY, WAS DISASSEMBLED, AND THE BURST DISC REPLACED WITH A LIKE TYPE 165 POUND ZOOK DISC. THE SAFETY VENT WAS REASSEMBLED AND THE REMAINING VALVES AND FITTINGS INSPECTED AND FOUND TO BE SECURE. IT APPEARS THE CAR HAD BEEN ROUGH HANDLED CAUSING A LIQUID SURGE THROUGH THE SAFETY VENT. THE CAR WAS THEN RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT ONTO THE CONSIGNEE. NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE TO CHEMTREC FOR REPORTING PURPOSES, AND THE SHIPPER AS INFORMATION.

column42: PETROLEUM GASES, LIQUEFIED OR LIQUEFIED PETROLEUM GAS
column168: ART THOMASON, CAR FOREMAN, REPORTED TANKCAR GATX 78010 RELEASED A GAS ODOR INSIDE THE RIPP TRACKS ON YARD 8, TRACK 502. THE TANKCAR WAS PLACED ON THE REPAIR TRACKS TO AWAIT THE ARRIVAL OF A CHEMICAL AGENT TO INSPECT IT. HARRY RODABOUGH CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY MANAGER, WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED. THE A END LIQUID VALVE WAS SLIGHTLY OPENED AND THE PLUG WAS UNSECURED. MR. RODABOUGH CLOSED THE VALVE, PULLED THE PLUG, APPLIED TEFLON TAPE TO THE PLUG AND SECURED THE PLUG. THE CAR WAS RELEASED FOR TRANSPORTATION.

DEAN C. COOPER. MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY WAS CONTACTED BY RMCC REPORTING A LEAKING TANK CAR IN THE COLTON YARD. MANAGER COOPER CONTACTED ROBERT SCHUT, MANAGER, TERMINAL OPERATIONS, WHO STATED THE CAR HAD BEEN REPORTED LEAKING BY THE TRIM JOB. MANAGER SCHUT FURTHER STATED HE HAD DRIVEN TO THE EAST END OF THE BOWL TRACKS AND OBSERVED A PLUME OF VAPOR RISING FROM THE TANK CAR. PRODUCT APPEARED TO BE LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM PORTION OF THE TANK CAR. MANAGER COOPER DROVE TO THE COLTON YARD AND MET WITH RIALTO FIRE DEPARTMENT OPERATIONS CHIEF, WHO HAD SET UP A COMMAND POST WEST OF THE TRIM TOWER. A VISIBLE PLUME OF VAPOR WAS OBSERVED RISING APPROXIMATELY 150 FEET INTO THE AIR. AT THE TIME, THE WINDS WERE CALM. THE FIRE DEPARTMENT HAD MADE AN ENTRY TO ASSESS THE LEAKING TANK CAR, AND FROM THE INITIAL REPORTS, IT WAS DETERMINED THE LEAK WAS COMING FROM THE BOTTOM SKID PLATE OF THE TANK CAR. MANAGER COOPER MADE A FOLLOW UP ENTRY TO INSPECT THE TANK CAR AND CONFIRMED THAT THE PRODUCT WAS COMING FROM THE BOTTOM SKID PLATE, WHICH WAS TOTALLY ENCLOSED, THUS PREVENTING ANY FURTHER OBSERVATION OF THE SUMP AREA OF THE CAR. THE SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED AND SEVERAL OPTIONS WERE DISCUSSED ON THE BEST WAY TO REMOVE THE PRODUCT FROM THE TANK CAR, AS IT APPEARED THE LINER HAD FAILED, AND THERE WAS NO WAY TO EFFECTIVELY STOP THE LEAK AND CONTAIN THE PRODUCT WITHIN THE CAR. ARRANGEMENTS WERE MADE TO OBTAIN THE SERVICES FROM SEVERAL OF THE RAILROAD'S HAZARDOUS MATERIAL CONTRACTORS, WHICH ALSO INCLUDED AIR MONITORING. ATTEMPTS TO LOCATE ENOUGH LINED ACID HIGHWAY TRUCKS MET WITH NEGATIVE RESULTS.  A CHECK OF THE YARD LOCATED A LIKE TYPE RAIL TANK CAR, WHICH ALSO BELONGED TO THE SHIPPER.  THE RESIDUE CAR, UTLX 802765, WAS ON AN ADJACENT BOWL TRACK, APPROXIMATELY 10 CAR LENGTHS WEST OF THE LEAKING TANK CAR. ENTRY WAS MADE TO FACILTATE THE REMOVAL OF THE RESIDUE CAR, WHICH WAS SET TO THE LEAD TRACK, WHERE IT COULD BE INSPECTED AND PLUMBED TO RECEIVE THE PRODUCT. ONCE THE TRANSFER OPERATION WAS IN PLACE, THE LEAKING TANK CAR WAS MOVED TO AN ADJACENT TRACK, WHERE IT WAS PLUMBED FOR THE TRANSFER. CONTAINMENT POOLS WERE PLACED UNDER THE LEAKING TANK CAR TO CAPTURE THE PRODUCT LEAKING FROM THE SKID PLATE WHILE THE TRANSFER WAS IN OPERATION. THE PRODUCT FROM THE CONTAINMENT POOLS WERE CAPTURED AND PLACED INTO A HIGHWAY TRUCK. ONCE THE TRANSFER OPERATION STARTED, CREWS WERE MOVED INTO BOWL TRACK 26, WHERE THE PRODUCT ON THE GROUND WAS NEUTRALIZED WITH SODA ASH. ONCE THE AREA WAS NEUTRALIZED, THE RESIDUE WAS PLACED INTO 55  GALLON DRUMS FOR TEMPORARY STORAGE PENDING DISPOSAL. ONCE THE TRANSFER OPERATION WAS COMPLETED, THE DAMAGED RAIL CAR WAS MOVED TO THE GATX TANK CAR REPAIR FACILITY LOCATED AT THE EAST END OF THE YARD, WHERE IT COULD BE INSPECTED AND REPAIRED. THE HIGHWAY TRUCK WILL BE DELIVERED TO PIONEER'S FACILITY ON MONDAY, AND THE LOADED TANK CAR WILL BE SCHEDULED FOR MOVEMENT TO PIONEER ONCE IT IS WEIGHED. NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE TO CHEMTREC FOR REPORTING PURPOSES

MAY 12, 2000 07:20 MDT, INSPECTED AND FOUND THAT THE CAR WAS STILL LEAKING, NOTIFIED JACK CURREY, FARMLAND IND, THAT THE CAR WOULD HAVE TO BE TRANSLOADED. 12:00 BOB ITA, FARMLAND IND HAD ARRANGED FOR AN EMPTY CAR, ITLX 150022 WAS IN ROUTE AND WOULD ARRIVE OGDEN 2200 HOURS. CAR UTLX WAS MOVED TO TRACK 509, AWAY FROM WORKER AND AT A LOCATION WERE THE TRANSLOAD COULD BE PERFORMED, A PLASTIC BARREL WITH ABSORBENT MATERIAL WAS PLACED UNDER THE CAR TO CONTAIN THE LEAK. MAY 13, 2000 0730 HOURS, MET PACIFIC WEST AT RESPONSE TRUCK, ARRIVED OGDEN AT 0830 HOURS TO START TRANSLOAD CONTENTS. RICK SLOANE, CTS PORTLAND ARRIVED AT 0910 MDT. MR SLOANE FOUND THAT THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE FACE PLACE WAS LOOSE. MR SLOANE TIGHTEN SET SCREWS, INSTALLED A GASKET BETWEEN VALVE AND BLIND FLANGE. CAR WAS RELEASE AT 1145 HOUR TO CONTINUE ON TO DESTINATION. CONTACTED FARMLAND BY VOICE MAIL THAT THE CONTENTS WAS NOT TRANSLOADED AND REPAIRS WERE MADE TO UTLX 13857. RECOMMEND THAT BEFORE THE CAR IS LOADED THE VALVE BE INSPECTED.

AT 0115HRS ON 5-16-00, CTS MGR LERCH WAS CONTACTED BY THE RMCC AND ADVISED THAT MANAGER TRAIN OPERATIONS SPENCE MURRAY HAD REPORTED A LEAKING TANK CAR AT THE 36 STREET YARD; DENVER, CO. MILE POST .02, YARD 01, OUTBOUND TRACK 301. UPON ARRIVAL, MGR LERCH NOTED PRODUCT VENTING FROM UNDER THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING. CAR WAS ENTRAINED ON OUTBOUND TRAIN MDVNP-16. CONTINUED INSPECTION FURTHER REVEALED THAT THE PLUG TO THE SAMPLE LINE WAS LOOSE 1 TURN, HOWEVER NO RELEASE OF PRODUCT FROM THIS FITTING COULD BE DETECTED. PLUG TO SAMPLE LINE WAS TIGHTENED BY MGR LERCH. UPON SECURING ALL VALVES AND FITTINGS, CAR WAS SECURED FOR TRANSPORTATION. THERE WERE NO REPORTED INJURIES, DRAINS OR WATERWAYS IMPACTED RESULTING FROM THIS RELEASE. NOTIFICATIONS: 1130HRS, 5-17-00, AGRIUM US, RANDY HOLLAND, OPERATIONS SUPERVISOR.

MANAGER MECHANICAL MAINTENANCE, LONNIE MUSE NOTED A VAPOR CLOUD NEAR THE BOTTOM OF THE CAR AND A BLOCK OF ICE AROUND THE OUTLET PIPE. REEDER RESPONDED AND FOUND THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE WAS RELEASING PRODUCT. PRESSURE IN THE TANK WAS 27 PSI. NORMAL PRESSURE SHOULD NOT EXCEED 15 PSI. A TECHNICIAN FROM THE SHIPPER, AIR LIQUID SPECULATED THE CAR WAS OVERLOADED. A BLOWDOWN VALVE WAS OPENED AND THE CAR ALLOWED TO VENT TO THE ATMOSPHERE FOR APPROXIMATELY 20 MINUTES. THE PRESSURE THEN READ 15 PSI. THE CAR WAS RELEASED FOR NORMAL MOVEMENT WITH ONLY A MINOR DELAY. CHEMTREC AND THE SHIPPER WERE NOTIFIED.

column62: Defective Component or Device; Corrosion - Exterior; Water Damage
column168: DEAN C. COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS CONTACTED BY RMCC REPORTING A LEAKING TANK CARS IN PHOENIX, ARIZONA. MANAGER COOPER CONTACTED MIKE SUMMERS, YARDMASTER, PHOENIX, WHO STATED THE CAR WAS BEING HANDLED DURING NORMAL SWITCHING OPERATIONS WHEN A SWITCHMAN WAS SPLASHED WITH PRODUCT COMING FROM THE TOP AREA OF THE CAR.  THE CAR WAS SET OUT NEXT TO THE TOWER WHERE IT COULD BE ISOLATED PENDING INSPECTION.  THE SWITCHMAN WAS TRANSPORTED TO THE LOCAL HOSPITAL FOR TREATMENT.  MANAGER COOPER CONTACTED ERI, THE RAILROAD'S HAZARDOUS MATERIAL CONTRACTOR IN PHOENIX, AND REQUESTED THEY RESPOND TO THE SITE AND DEVELOP THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK. INSPECTION OF THE CAR DEVELOPED THE LEAK WAS FROM THE LIQUID EDUCTION LINE LOCATED NEXT TO THE MANWAY.  THE LIQUID LINE NOZZLE FROM THE TOP OF THE CAR HAS A 6 INCH FLANGE, WHERE THE 2 INCH LIQUID LINE CONNECTION IS ATTACHED.  THE 4 BOLTS THAT SECURE THE FLANGES WERE CORRODED AT THE THREADS WHERE THE NUTS TIGHTEN AGAINST THE FLANGES.  ALL BOLTS COULD BE TURNED BY HAND, AND ATTEMPTS TO TIGHTEN THE BOLTS FAILED DUE TO THE DETERIORATED THREADS.  THE BOLTS WERE REMOVED AND THE FLANGE SPEARATED TO INSPECT THE GASKET, WHICH WAS FOUND TO BE BROKEN INTO 2 SEPARATE PIECES.  A TEMPORARY GASKET WAS FABRICATED, AND THE FLANGE REINSTALLED UTILIZING 4 REPLACEMENT BOLTS, NUTS AND WASHERS.  THE SURFACE OF THE TANK CAR WAS CLEANED TO REMOVE THE RESIDUE PRODUCT.  THE CAR WAS THEN MOVED SEVERAL TIMES TO INSURE PROPER SECURMENT, AND THEN RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT ONTO THE LOCAL CONSIGNEE.  NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE TO CHEMTREC FOR REPORTING PURPOSES, AND THE SHIPPER FOR CORRECTIVE ACTION.
TANK CAR WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING VAPORS FROM THE MANWAY DUE TO UNTIGHTENED MANWAY BOLTS.MANWAY BOLTS WERE TIGHTENED AND THE CAR WAS RELEASED TO CONTINUE IN TRANSPORTATION.

column168: MGR. C.T.S. R. SLOANE WAS NOTIFIED BY YARD FORCES AT HINKLE OF A LEAK COMING FROM THE TOP OF TANK CAR PROX 40699.  THE TANK CAR WAS LEAKING IN THE AREA OF THE COMBINATION FITTINGS HOUSING AT A RATE OF ABOUT A CUP AN HOUR.  THE TEMPERATURE WAS APPROXIMATELY 82 DEG. F, AND WINDS WERE LIGHT, 5 - 8 MPH FROM THE NE.  MR. SLOANE RESPONDED AND INSPECTED THE CAR.  MR. SLOANE OBSERVED A RELEASE OF "A FEW DROPS A MINUTE" FROM THE FLANGE UPON WHICH THE AIR AND LIQUID EDUCTION ARE MOUNTED.  MR. SLOANE RELEASED PRESSURE FROM THE CAR VIA THE VACUUM BREAKER VALVE AND REMOVED THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING FROM THE VALVES.  THE AIR LINE WAS SECURE BUT THE LIQUID EDUCTION VALVE (3' IN LINE BALL VALVE) WAS NOT TIGHTLY THREADED ONTO THE ATTACHMENT NIPPLE.THIS RESULTED IN THE RELEASE OF THE COMMODITY WHEN THE INTERNAL PRESSURE WAS SUFFICIENT TO FORCE LIQUID UP THE EDUCTION LINE TO THE VALVE.  MR. SLOANE REMOVED THE VALVE, WRAPPED THE NIPPLE THREADS WITH TEFLON TAPE AND PROPERLY SECURED THE VALVE.  ALL OTHER FITTING WERE ALSO CHECKED FOR SECUREMENT WITH NO EXCEPTIONS.

UPRR RMCC NOTIFIED MR.JOHN JACKSON,MGR.CTS-EL PASO,THAT TANK CAR DOWX 6864 WAS LEAKING PRODUCT FROM BOTTOM OF CAR.THE CAR WAS BEING ISOLATED TO TRACK 503 IN BIG SPRINGS,TX. MR JACKSON CONFERED WITH MR MIKE QUISENBERRY,AGENT DOW CHEMICAL.MR QUISENBERRY STATED HE WOULD MOBLIZE A CREW FOR REPAIRS AND CLEANUP.MR. JACKSON ARRIVED AT THE SCENE,INSPECTED THE CAR AND FOUND THE INNER LINER HAD FAILED AND PRODUCT HAD CORRODED THROUGH THE TANK SHELL ON THE BOTTOM.CONSIGNEE,REAGENT CHEMICAL,WAS IN THE PROCESS OF TRANSFERING PRODUCTS INTO TRUCKS.ALL THE PRODUCT WAS TRANSFERED AND SENT TO REAGENT'S PLANT.THE CAR WAS NEUTRALIZED AND PURGED WITH A WATER AND SODA SOLUTION AND SENT TO HOME SHOP FOR REPAIRS.

MR. JEFF WALKER MYO-EL PASO NOTIFIED MR. JOHN JACKSON AND UPRR RMCC THAT TANK CAR UTLX 48743 WAS LEAKING PRODUCT FROM THE TOP OF CAR. MR. JACKSON RESPONDED, INSPECTED THE CAR AND FOUND IT TO BE OVERLOADED.  MR. JACKSON CONFERENCED WITH SHIPPER, MR. RON ERICSON, COASTAL CHEM.  MR. ERICSON STATED HE WOULD CONTRACT THE CONSIGNEE, NAVAJO REFINERY TO RESPOND.  NAVAJO REPRESENTITIVE, LINDA SANDY RESPONDED AND INSPECTED THE CAR.  MS. SANDY STATED SHE WOULD CONTRACT C&R PETROLEUM TO SUPPLY A TRUCK TO PUMP SOME OF THE PRODUCT OFF AND SHIP TO THE NAVAJO PLANT.  APPROX. 7,000 GALLONS WERE TRANSFERED TO THE C&R TRUCK AND SHIPPED TO NAVAJO'S PLANT AT ASHLEY, TX.  NAVAJO PERSONAL SECURED THE TANKCAR AND MR. JACKSON RELEASED IT FOR TRANSPORTATION.

column168: DEAN C COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS CONTACTED BY RMCC REPORTING A DERAILMENT AT THE CAMERON CROSSOVER, 12 MILES NORTH OF MOJAVE.  DEVELOPED THE MWCRV-24 (WESTBOUND) HAD DERAILED AT THE CROSSOVER FROM THE #2 MAINLINE.  SEVERAL CARS WERE INVOLVED IN THE DERAILMENT, INCLUDING THE ABOVE TANK CAR THAT WAS REPORTED ON IT'S SIDE AND LEAKING.  NO ADDITIONAL DETAILS WERE AVAILABLE AT THE TIME.  MANAGER COOPER DROVE TO THE DERAILMENT SITE AND MET WITH THE KERN COUNTY FIRE DEPARTMENT HAZARDOUS MATERIALS TEAM, WHO MADE A PRELIMINARY ENTRY TO ASSESS THE ABOVE TANK CAR AND SEVERAL OTHER RAILCARS.  DEVELOPED THE ABOVE TANK CAR WAS LEAKING FROM THE GENERAL AREA WHERE THE LIQUID EDUCTION LINE AND AIR LINE ARE LOCATED.  AS THE PROTECTIVE COVER WAS IN PLACE, THE TEAM WAS NOT ABLE TO DETERMINE THE EXACT LOCATION OF THE LEAK.  AFTER SOME DISCUSSION WITH THE FIRE DEPARTMENT, IT WAS DECIDED TO MAKE A SECOND ENTRY WITH SOME TOOLS AND ATTEMPT TO STOP THE LEAK.  MANAGER COOPER, IN COMPANY WITH THE KERN COUNTY HAZMAT TEAM, MADE ENTRY TO THE CAR, WHICH WAS LAYING ON IT'S LEFT SIDE AT AT 90 DEGREE ANGLE.  THE PROTECTIVE COVER FOR THE LIQUID LINE WAS OPENED, AND DEVELOPED THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK TO BE FROM THE FLANGE ON THE LIQUID EDUCTION LINE WHERE IT BOLTS TO THE NOZZLE PLATE.  WHILE ALL 4 OF THE MOUNTING NUTS APPEARED TO BE TIGHT, THEY COULD BE TURNED AN ADDITIONAL HALF TURN.  THE TIGHTENING OF THE BOLTS SLOWED THE LEAK TO A STEADY DRIP ESTIMATED TO BE ONE GALLON EVERY 4-5 MINUTES.  IT APPEARED THE FLANGE GASKET WAS DETERIORATED AND WOULD NOT HOLD THE HEAD PRESSURE OF THE LIQUID.  IT WAS DECIDED ANY FURTHER TIGHTENING OF THE NUTS TO CONTROL THE LEAK COULD SNAP THE STUDS.  INSPECTION OF THE BOTTOM OUTLET FOUND THE NOZZLE BELOW THE SKID PLATE HAD BEEN SHEARED OFF. THE INTERNAL BALL VALVE WAS VISIBLE AND WAS DRIPPING PRODUCT AT A RATE OF APPROXIMATELY ONE GALLON EVERY 2-3 MINUTES.  ATTEMPTS TO SLOW THE LEAK BY ADJUSTING THE BALL VALVE, AND EVEN APPLYING PUTTY AROUND THE VALVE FAILED.  ONCE THE FIRE DEPARTMENT HAD MONITORED THE AREA AND AGREED ON THE REMEDIAITION EFFORT, THEY DEPARTED THE SCENE. ARRANGEMENTS WERE MADE TO RIGHT THE TANK CAR AND MOVE IT TO THE SOUTH SIDE OF THE #2 THE FIRST TRANSFER OPERATION STARTING AT 7:45AM.  THE LAST TRUCK WAS FINALLY LOADED AT 1:00PM.  ARRANGEMENTS WERE MADE WITH THE ORIGINAL AREA WHERE THE TANK CAR HAD LEAKED DURING THE INITIAL DERAILMENT, AND IN THE AREA WHERE THE CAR HAD BEEN STAGED FOR THE TRANSFER.  REMEDIATION WILL BE ADDRESSED BASED UPON THE ANALYTICAL RESULTS.  NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE TO CHEMTREC FOR REPORTING PURPOSES, AND THE SHIPPER FOR CORRECTIVE ACTION.

MGR. WILDER WAS NOTIFIED THAT CONTAINER MOGU 207342 HAD LEAKED, BUT THERE WAS NO PRODUCT ON THE GROUND. THE SHIPPER MOL INTERMODAL  WAS NOTIFIED OF THE SPILL AND RESPONDED WITH THEIR HAZMAT TEAM ( HEARTLAND ENVIRONMENTAL). HEARTLAND TRANSFERRED THE CONTAINER AND SECURED THE LOAD. AVAILABLE INFORMATION INDICATED THAT ONE PAIL HAD BEEN ABRAIDED DURING SHIPMENT.

column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 10PM ON 5/22/2000 A TANKCAR EMITTED VAPORS IN THE A&S RAIL YARD IN EAST ST. LOUIS, II.  JOHN MILLER ENVIRONMENTAL MGR. RESPONDED TO THE SCENE AND CALLED ON HULCHER ENVIRONMENTAL TO HELP WITH HANDLING OF THE INCIDENT.  INSPECTION OF THE CAR SHOWED THAT THE MANWAY COVER WAS LOOSE AND THE MANWAY GASKET WAS OUT OF PLACE. HULCHER PERSONNEL OPENED THE MANWAY COVER AND REFITTED THE GASKET AND TIGHTENED THE BOLTS.  MIKE SEABAUGH MGR. OF CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY HAD ALSO RESPONDED ALONG WITH AN AIR MONITORING CONTRACTOR FROM NORTH LITTLE ROCK, ARKANSAS.  UPON COMPLETION OF THE WORK ON THE CAR, THE AIR IN THE SURROUNDING AREA WAS MONITORED FOR RESIDUAL VAPORS.  THERE WERE NONE.  THE CAR WAS RELEASED AT 6AM ON THE MAY 23RD.
WHILE FILLING A RESIDENTIAL FUEL TANK, THERE WAS A SPILL DUE TO OVERFILLING.  EMPLOYEES NEED TO PAY CLOSER ATTENTION TO SITUATION.
